INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Understanding Your Prenatal Visit Schedule',
  'prenatal-visit-schedule',
  'Learn what to expect during each trimester of prenatal care and why regular monitoring is essential for maternal and fetal health.',
  E'# Understanding Your Prenatal Visit Schedule\n\nRegular prenatal visits form the foundation of a healthy pregnancy. These appointments allow healthcare providers to monitor your wellbeing, track fetal development, and identify potential complications early.\n\n## First Trimester (Weeks 1-13)\n\nYour initial visit is typically the most comprehensive. Your provider will take a detailed medical and obstetric history, perform a complete physical examination, and establish baseline measurements. Dating ultrasound helps confirm gestational age and identify multiple pregnancies. Initial lab work screens for blood type, anemia, infections, and genetic markers. After this appointment, visits typically occur monthly until week 28.\n\n## Second Trimester (Weeks 14-27)\n\nMonthly visits continue with regular blood pressure monitoring, weight checks, and urine screening. The anatomy ultrasound between 18-22 weeks provides detailed evaluation of fetal organs and placental position. Glucose screening around week 24 helps identify gestational diabetes. These visits allow discussion of symptoms like swelling, heartburn, and musculoskeletal discomfort.\n\n## Third Trimester (Weeks 28-40)\n\nVisit frequency increases to every two weeks beginning at week 28, then weekly from week 36 onward. Assessment includes checking fetal position, estimating fetal weight through measurement, and evaluating cervical changes. Non-stress testing may begin at week 36 to monitor fetal heart rate patterns. These frequent visits help identify complications like preeclampsia, growth concerns, or labor onset.\n\n## What Happens During Each Visit\n\nStandard components include blood pressure monitoring to screen for hypertension, weight assessment to track appropriate gain, and urine testing for protein and glucose. Fundal height measurement correlates with gestational age and fetal growth. Fetal heart rate monitoring begins around week 12 and continues throughout pregnancy. Your provider will discuss symptoms, answer questions, and provide guidance on nutrition, activity, and preparation for birth.\n\n## When Additional Visits May Be Needed\n\nComplicating factors like hypertension, diabetes, previous pregnancy loss, or advanced maternal age may require more frequent monitoring or specialist consultation. Bleeding, severe pain, vision changes, or decreased fetal movement warrant urgent evaluation regardless of scheduled appointment timing.',
  'article',
  'https://www.acog.org/womens-health/faqs/prenatal-care',
  -40,
  0,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Nutrition During Pregnancy: Essential Nutrients',
  'nutrition-pregnancy-essential-nutrients',
  'Discover the key nutrients your body needs during pregnancy and practical approaches to meeting your nutritional requirements.',
  E'# Nutrition During Pregnancy: Essential Nutrients\n\nProper nutrition during pregnancy directly impacts fetal development, maternal health, and birth outcomes. Rather than eating for two, focus on eating well to support both your body and your developing baby.\n\n## Caloric Needs\n\nCaloric requirements increase modestly during pregnancy, with no additional calories needed in the first trimester. The second and third trimesters require approximately 340 and 450 additional calories daily, respectively. However, individual needs vary based on pre-pregnancy weight, activity level, and whether carrying multiples. Quality matters more than quantity—prioritize nutrient-dense foods over empty calories.\n\n## Protein Requirements\n\nProtein needs increase from 46 grams daily for non-pregnant women to 71 grams during pregnancy. Adequate protein supports tissue growth, enzyme production, and antibody formation. Include varied sources: lean meats, poultry, fish, eggs, legumes, nuts, seeds, and dairy products. Vegetarian and vegan pregnancies can meet protein needs through complementary plant proteins, though careful planning ensures adequate micronutrient intake.\n\n## Critical Micronutrients\n\nFolic acid supplementation (400-800 micrograms daily) reduces birth defect risk, particularly neural tube defects. Iron requirements increase to 27 milligrams daily; anemia is common and impacts fetal oxygenation. Calcium needs remain 1000 milligrams daily; adequate intake supports fetal skeletal development and protects maternal bone health. Iodine (220 micrograms daily) is essential for fetal neurological development. Vitamin D supports calcium absorption; safe sun exposure and fortified foods contribute to adequate levels.\n\n## DHA and Brain Development\n\nDocosahexaenoic acid (DHA), an omega-3 fatty acid, supports fetal brain and eye development. Include sources like fatty fish (limited to 2-3 servings weekly due to mercury concerns), marine supplements, or fortified foods. The combination of adequate omega-3 intake and other micronutrients optimizes neurodevelopmental outcomes.\n\n## Foods to Limit or Avoid\n\nLimit caffeine to less than 200 milligrams daily. Avoid high-mercury fish including shark, swordfish, and king mackerel. Raw or undercooked animal products carry listeria risk; avoid unpasteurized dairy, deli meats, and raw fish. Alcohol carries teratogenic risks at any amount; complete abstinence is recommended.\n\n## Practical Strategies\n\nConsume foods across all food groups daily. Include whole grains, colorful vegetables and fruits, lean proteins, dairy or fortified alternatives, and healthy fats. Prenatal vitamins supplement but do not replace a balanced diet. Regular small meals prevent nausea and maintain stable blood sugar. Stay hydrated with 8-10 glasses of water daily.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.acog.org/womens-health/faqs/nutrition-during-pregnancy',
  -40,
  0,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Managing Common Pregnancy Discomforts',
  'managing-pregnancy-discomforts',
  'Understand why discomforts occur during pregnancy and learn evidence-based strategies for safe and effective relief.',
  E'# Managing Common Pregnancy Discomforts\n\nPhysical changes during pregnancy can create discomfort as your body adapts to support a growing baby. Understanding the causes helps you address symptoms effectively and distinguish normal discomfort from warning signs.\n\n## Nausea and Vomiting\n\nFirst trimester nausea affects approximately 80% of pregnant people. Small, frequent meals prevent stomach emptiness, which worsens nausea. Ginger in food, beverages, or supplement form shows evidence of benefit. Vitamin B6 (50-100 milligrams daily) reduces nausea severity. Acupressure wristbands may provide relief. Severe vomiting causing dehydration or weight loss requires medical evaluation; medication options are available and safe.\n\n## Heartburn and Indigestion\n\nProgesterone relaxes the esophageal sphincter, allowing stomach acid reflux. Avoid large meals, spicy foods, and eating close to bedtime. Eat slowly and chew thoroughly. Antacids containing calcium carbonate or magnesium are safe options. Raise your head while sleeping. Avoid lying down immediately after eating.\n\n## Back and Pelvic Pain\n\nWeight gain, postural changes, and hormone-induced ligament relaxation contribute to discomfort. Supportive, low-heeled shoes distribute weight properly. Pelvic support garments reduce strain. Prenatal yoga and swimming strengthen supporting muscles. Heating pads provide temporary relief. Physical therapy can address specific pain patterns. Sleep positions matter—side-sleeping with a pillow between knees reduces stress on the pelvis.\n\n## Swelling and Leg Cramps\n\nSwelling occurs as pregnancy hormones increase sodium retention and fluid shifts to tissues. Elevate legs regularly, stay hydrated, and wear compression stockings if recommended. Leg cramps may indicate dehydration or electrolyte imbalance; stretching calf muscles before bed can reduce frequency. Ensure adequate calcium and magnesium intake. Nighttime cramps deserve discussion with your provider.\n\n## Sleep Disruptions\n\nProgesterone affects sleep architecture, and physical discomfort interferes with rest. Establish consistent sleep routines. Support pillows under the belly and between knees improve comfort. Room temperature, darkness, and quiet support better sleep. Limit fluids before bed to reduce nighttime bathroom trips. Relaxation techniques and prenatal yoga facilitate sleep.\n\n## Varicose Veins and Hemorrhoids\n\nIncreased blood volume and hormone effects weaken vessel walls. Elevate legs, avoid standing for prolonged periods, and wear compression stockings. Adequate fiber and hydration prevent constipation, which worsens hemorrhoids. Warm (not hot) sitz baths provide relief. Most resolve after delivery.\n\n## When to Seek Care\n\nDifferentiate discomfort from warning signs: severe abdominal pain, persistent vomiting preventing food intake, swelling in face or hands, severe headache, vision changes, or vaginal bleeding warrant immediate evaluation.',
  'article',
  'https://www.acog.org/womens-health/faqs/managing-pregnancy-discomfort',
  -40,
  0,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Preparing for Labor and Delivery',
  'preparing-labor-delivery',
  'Get comprehensive information about labor stages, delivery options, pain management approaches, and what to expect during childbirth.',
  E'# Preparing for Labor and Delivery\n\nUnderstanding labor and delivery helps you prepare emotionally and physically for birth. Knowledge reduces anxiety and empowers you to make informed decisions aligned with your preferences and medical needs.\n\n## Three Stages of Labor\n\nLabor begins when uterine contractions occur at regular intervals with cervical changes. The first stage, latent phase, involves cervical dilation to 3 centimeters. Contractions occur every 5-20 minutes and feel manageable. The active phase starts at 3 centimeters dilation and progresses to 7 centimeters; contractions intensify and come every 2-3 minutes. The transition phase, 7-10 centimeters, is the most intense portion, lasting 15 minutes to a few hours.\n\nThe second stage begins at full cervical dilation and involves pushing until delivery. Contractions become more purposeful, and your body''s natural urges guide pushing efforts. This stage typically lasts 20 minutes to 2 hours for first-time parents. The third stage involves delivery of the placenta, lasting 5-30 minutes.\n\n## Pain Management Options\n\nNon-pharmacological approaches include position changes, continuous support from a partner or doula, breathing techniques, and hydrotherapy. Many hospitals offer nitrous oxide inhalation, providing relief while allowing participation. Epidural anesthesia blocks sensation from the waist down, allowing rest during long labor. Spinal blocks provide rapid relief for operative delivery. Discuss preferences with your provider during pregnancy; flexibility allows adjustment based on labor progression.\n\n## Vaginal Delivery\n\nMost pregnancies progress to spontaneous vaginal delivery. Your provider guides pushing efforts. Perineal support during delivery reduces tearing severity. Controlled delivery of the baby''s head allows gradual stretching. Some tearing may occur; most heal well. Immediate skin-to-skin contact supports bonding and breastfeeding initiation.\n\n## Assisted Vaginal Delivery\n\nWhen pushing efforts or baby''s positioning delay progress, vacuum or forceps assistance may expedite delivery. These instruments are safe when used appropriately and avoid the recovery period associated with cesarean delivery.\n\n## Cesarean Delivery\n\nAbdominal surgical delivery becomes necessary for certain complications: failure to progress, fetal distress, placental problems, or cord prolapse. Scheduled cesarean delivery occurs before labor for factors like placenta previa or breech presentation. Recovery involves abdominal and uterine incisions; hospital stay lasts 2-3 days, and activity restrictions continue 4-6 weeks. Risks include infection and hemorrhage, but maternal outcomes are generally good with appropriate medical care.\n\n## What to Bring and Expect\n\nBring insurance information, identification, and any hospital pre-registration documents. Comfortable labor gowns, entertainment, and comfort items support your experience. A support person should plan to stay; hospitals provide accommodations. Expect frequent monitoring of contractions and fetal heart rate. Eating and drinking policies vary; discuss with your provider. Pain management options become available as labor progresses.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.acog.org/womens-health/faqs/labor-delivery-and-postpartum-care',
  -36,
  0,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Prenatal Screening and Genetic Testing Options',
  'prenatal-screening-genetic-testing',
  'Learn about screening tests available during pregnancy to assess fetal health and understand what results mean for your pregnancy.',
  E'# Prenatal Screening and Genetic Testing Options\n\nPrenatal screening helps identify pregnancies at increased risk for certain conditions, allowing informed decision-making and appropriate planning. Understanding available options, what they measure, and their accuracy helps you choose approaches aligned with your values.\n\n## Screening Versus Diagnostic Testing\n\nScreening tests estimate risk but do not diagnose. They have false positive and false negative rates. Diagnostic tests confirm or exclude conditions but carry small miscarriage risks. Understanding this distinction helps you interpret results appropriately and decide whether diagnostic confirmation is desired.\n\n## First Trimester Combined Screening\n\nBetween 11-14 weeks, maternal blood screening measures pregnancy-associated plasma protein-A (PAPP-A) and human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG). Transvaginal ultrasound measures nuchal translucency, fluid thickness at the fetal neck. This combination detects 90% of Down syndrome cases with 5% false positive rate. Results are reported as risk estimates, not definitive diagnoses.\n\n## Second Trimester Screening\n\nQuadruple screening uses maternal serum markers measured between 15-22 weeks: alpha-fetoprotein, hCG, unconjugated estriol, and inhibin A. This combination detects 80% of Down syndrome cases. Sequential screening combines first and second trimester results for enhanced detection. Integrated screening combines all markers for optimal accuracy while minimizing false positives.\n\n## Detailed Anatomy Ultrasound\n\nThe 18-22 week ultrasound evaluates fetal organ development, heart structure, brain anatomy, spine alignment, limb development, and placental position. Ultrasound is non-invasive with no known risks. This scan identifies major structural anomalies and informs decision-making. Three-dimensional ultrasound provides additional detail when indicated.\n\n## Noninvasive Prenatal Testing (NIPT)\n\nCell-free DNA testing analyzes fetal DNA in maternal blood, performed from 9 weeks onward. This highly accurate screening detects Down syndrome, Edwards syndrome, and Patau syndrome with 99% sensitivity and 99.5% specificity for Down syndrome. NIPT can also reveal sex and assess fetal fraction adequacy. Results typically available within 7-10 days. This test is optional and appropriate for those seeking early, accurate risk assessment.\n\n## Diagnostic Testing Options\n\nAmniotic fluid sampling (amniocentesis) performed after 15 weeks analyzes fetal chromosomes with 99.4% accuracy. Procedure involves ultrasound-guided needle insertion; miscarriage risk is approximately 1 in 500. Chorionic villus sampling (CVS) at 10-13 weeks offers earlier diagnosis but carries similar miscarriage risk. Both require genetic counseling before and after testing.\n\n## Informed Decision-Making\n\nGenetic counseling explores family history, testing options, potential results, and implications. Counselors help clarify your values and preferences. Not all pregnant people choose screening; some prefer knowing only what becomes apparent at birth. Others seek early diagnosis to prepare psychologically and medically. There is no single correct choice; individual values guide decisions.',
  'article',
  'https://www.acog.org/womens-health/faqs/prenatal-screening-options',
  -40,
  -20,
  'published',
  false
);

-- Postpartum Care Resources
INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Your Body After Birth: Physical Recovery Timeline',
  'postpartum-physical-recovery-timeline',
  'Understand the physical changes your body undergoes after birth and what to expect during the recovery period.',
  E'# Your Body After Birth: Physical Recovery Timeline\n\nPostpartum recovery is a gradual process requiring patience and self-care. Knowledge about normal changes helps you recognize warning signs and support your body''s healing.\n\n## Days 1-3: Immediate Postpartum\n\nThe first 24-48 hours involve significant fluid shifts as your body eliminates excess pregnancy fluid through increased urination and perspiration. Lochia, vaginal discharge containing blood and uterine lining, begins as heavy, bright red bleeding that gradually decreases over weeks. Perineal pain occurs from stretching, tearing, or episiotomy. Ice packs reduce swelling; sitting on inflatable cushions provide comfort. Afterpains—uterine contractions—intensify during breastfeeding as oxytocin promotes uterine involution. These are strongest in the first 3 days and decrease thereafter.\n\nBowel and bladder function normalize gradually. Hemorrhoid pain, stool softeners, increased fiber and fluids ease bowel function. Voiding pain from perineal stretching is common; running warm water over the perineum reduces discomfort. Contact your provider if you cannot void within 6-8 hours postpartum.\n\n## Week 1: Early Recovery\n\nUterine involution progresses; your provider can feel the uterus decreasing in size during postpartum visits. Vaginal bleeding remains moderate but gradually changes to brownish discharge. Perineal discomfort peaks around day 3-4, then gradually improves. Continue cold therapy and warm sitz baths. Kegel exercises promote pelvic floor healing, beginning gently when comfortable.\n\nChest engorgement occurs 2-3 days postpartum as milk production establishes; breasts become full, tender, and warm. Cold compresses, supportive bras, and occasional expression provide relief. Pain with breastfeeding should improve by day 7 if latch is appropriate; lactation consultation helps if pain persists.\n\n## Weeks 2-4: Continued Healing\n\nVaginal bleeding decreases but persists for 4-6 weeks. Perineal healing accelerates; most minor tears heal by 2 weeks. Sexual intercourse generally safely resumes 4-6 weeks postpartum once bleeding significantly decreases and perineal pain resolves, but individual healing varies. Discuss with your provider before resuming intercourse.\n\nMood fluctuations are normal. The postpartum blues—temporary sadness, crying, and mood lability—affect 60-80% of new mothers, peaking around days 3-5 and typically resolving within 2 weeks. Support from family and partners helps; these feelings differ from postpartum depression or anxiety.\n\n## Weeks 6-12: Ongoing Recovery\n\nMost vaginal discharge resolves by 4-6 weeks. Some brown spotting may continue. Complete perineal healing occurs by 6 weeks. Your provider evaluates healing at the 6-week postpartum visit. Diastasis recti—abdominal muscle separation—gradually improves; core-strengthening exercises initiated after 6 weeks, when cleared by your provider, support recovery. Many women feel physically recovered by 8-10 weeks, though complete recovery takes longer.\n\n## When to Seek Immediate Care\n\nCall your provider or seek emergency care for heavy vaginal bleeding soaking multiple pads hourly, severe abdominal pain, signs of infection including fever and chills, leg pain or swelling, shortness of breath, chest pain, thoughts of harming yourself or your baby, or inability to care for yourself.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.acog.org/womens-health/faqs/postpartum-care-faqs',
  0,
  12,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Recognizing Postpartum Depression and Anxiety',
  'postpartum-depression-anxiety',
  'Learn the signs of postpartum depression and anxiety, risk factors that increase vulnerability, and effective treatment options.',
  E'# Recognizing Postpartum Depression and Anxiety\n\nPostpartum mood disorders affect a significant portion of new mothers. Early recognition and treatment lead to excellent outcomes, but stigma and underdiagnosis delay care. Understanding these conditions helps you recognize symptoms and seek appropriate support.\n\n## Postpartum Blues Versus Depression\n\nPostpartum blues occur in 50-80% of new mothers. Symptoms include mood swings, irritability, crying, and sadness beginning days 2-5 and resolving within 2 weeks. These represent normal physiological response to hormonal shifts and sleep deprivation. Most improve with support, rest, and reassurance.\n\nPostpartum depression (PPD) affects 10-20% of new mothers. Onset can occur anytime in the postpartum year but typically begins within 4 weeks of delivery. Symptoms include persistent depressed mood, loss of interest in activities, fatigue, sleep disturbance, guilt, difficulty concentrating, and thoughts of worthlessness. Severe depression includes risk of self-harm or harm to the baby. PPD is a medical condition, not weakness or poor mothering.\n\n## Postpartum Anxiety Disorders\n\nPostpartum anxiety and OCD are often underrecognized but affect 10-15% of postpartum women. Generalized anxiety involves persistent worry about baby''s health, your competence as a mother, or catastrophic outcomes. Intrusive thoughts—unwanted, disturbing mental images—may cause intense distress despite knowing they don''t reflect your wishes. Panic attacks involve sudden intense fear, rapid heart rate, and physical symptoms. These conditions respond well to treatment but often go undiagnosed when attributed to normal new parent concerns.\n\n## Risk Factors\n\nPrevious depression or anxiety episodes, family history of mood disorders, relationship stress, lack of social support, and pregnancy complications increase risk. Difficult labor or delivery, separation from baby due to medical needs, and breastfeeding difficulties contribute to risk. Sleep deprivation potentiates all mood symptoms.\n\n## Seeking Help\n\nAll new mothers should be screened for depression and anxiety. Screening instruments like the Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale (EPDS) help identify at-risk individuals. If screening is positive or you notice concerning symptoms, contact your OB provider. Therapy, medication, and lifestyle changes effectively treat postpartum mood disorders. Cognitive-behavioral therapy is first-line treatment for anxiety. Antidepressants are safe during breastfeeding when appropriate ones are selected.\n\n## What Helps\n\nAdequate sleep supports mental health; accept help with household tasks and baby care to preserve sleep. Social support reduces isolation. Peer support groups connect you with others experiencing similar challenges. Exercise improves mood and anxiety symptoms. Partner involvement in baby care and household tasks reduces burden. Be compassionate with yourself; postpartum mood disorders are medical conditions, not personal failures.\n\n## When to Seek Immediate Help\n\nThoughts of harming yourself or your baby warrant immediate evaluation. Call 988 (Suicide and Crisis Lifeline) or go to the nearest emergency room. Contact your provider, a mental health professional, or a trusted person immediately. Perinatal mood and anxiety disorders are treatable; help is available.',
  'article',
  'https://www.acog.org/womens-health/faqs/postpartum-depression',
  0,
  52,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Postpartum Nutrition for Recovery and Breastfeeding',
  'postpartum-nutrition-recovery-breastfeeding',
  'Understand postpartum nutritional needs that support healing, energy recovery, and breastfeeding success.',
  E'# Postpartum Nutrition for Recovery and Breastfeeding\n\nYour nutritional needs remain elevated during postpartum recovery and breastfeeding. Prioritizing nutrition supports healing, energy restoration, and milk production if breastfeeding.\n\n## Caloric Needs\n\nPostpartum caloric requirements exceed non-pregnancy needs even without breastfeeding. The delivery process depletes energy reserves; healing requires adequate calories. Exclusive breastfeeding increases caloric needs by 300-500 calories daily, though individual requirements vary. Rather than restricting calories for postpartum weight loss, focus on nutrient-dense foods supporting healing and milk production. Gradual weight loss over months allows sustained energy and milk supply.\n\n## Protein for Tissue Healing\n\nProtein requirements increase to support uterine involution, perineal healing, and tissue repair. Aim for 75-100 grams daily, slightly above non-pregnancy requirements. Include varied sources: lean meats, poultry, fish, eggs, legumes, nuts, seeds, and dairy products. Adequate protein supports immune function and reduces infection risk.\n\n## Continued Micronutrient Needs\n\nIron losses from delivery are significant; postpartum iron needs remain elevated through 6 weeks. Continue iron supplementation if started prenatally, or increase dietary iron. Red meat, poultry, legumes, fortified grains, and dark leafy greens provide dietary iron. Vitamin C enhances iron absorption. Calcium remains important at 1000 milligrams daily, particularly if breastfeeding, as infant calcium requirements are met from maternal stores.\n\nIodine (290 micrograms daily) continues supporting your health and, if breastfeeding, your infant''s neurological development. Iodized salt, dairy, eggs, and seaweed provide iodine. Continue prenatal vitamins during breastfeeding, particularly for vitamin D, DHA, and B vitamins.\n\n## Hydration\n\nDehydration is common postpartum due to increased urination and perspiration. Drink to thirst, but aim for at least 8-10 glasses of water daily. Proper hydration supports healing, energy, and milk production. Drinking water before and during breastfeeding sessions ensures adequate intake. Limit caffeine to moderate amounts; excess caffeine passes to breast milk and may cause infant irritability.\n\n## Foods That May Help\n\nHistorically, warming foods and broths support recovery in many cultures. Bone broth, warm soups, and easily digested foods may feel comforting. Foods rich in iron and vitamin C—citrus fruits with red meat, berries with eggs—support healing. Oily fish and omega-3 rich foods support mood and neurological function. Foods with whole grains, legumes, and fiber prevent constipation, common postpartum.\n\n## Breastfeeding and Diet\n\nMost foods are safe while breastfeeding. Strongly flavored foods (garlic, onions, spices) may change milk flavor; babies often enjoy diverse flavors. Alcohol in moderation is compatible with breastfeeding; wait 2 hours per standard drink before nursing. High-mercury fish should remain limited. Caffeine passes to breast milk; moderate consumption (less than 300 milligrams daily) is safe. Cows milk allergy in babies may require maternal dairy elimination; consult your provider if you suspect sensitivity.\n\n## Practical Feeding Strategies\n\nEasy meals prepare during pregnancy. One-handed foods support eating while holding or nursing. Nutrient-dense snacks—nuts, cheese, fruit, yogurt—sustain energy throughout the day. Ask partners or family to prepare meals during early postpartum. Accepting help with cooking and cleaning preserves your energy for healing and baby care.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care/breastfeeding-resources/',
  0,
  26,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'When to Call Your Doctor: Postpartum Warning Signs',
  'postpartum-warning-signs-checklist',
  'A comprehensive checklist of symptoms requiring immediate medical evaluation during the postpartum recovery period.',
  E'# When to Call Your Doctor: Postpartum Warning Signs\n\nMost postpartum recoveries progress smoothly, but certain symptoms warrant immediate medical evaluation. Knowing warning signs helps you differentiate normal recovery from complications.\n\n## Bleeding Concerns\n\n- Heavy bleeding soaking more than one pad per hour for several hours\n- Bleeding that suddenly increases after decreasing\n- Bright red bleeding lasting more than a few days\n- Passage of clots larger than a plum\n- Foul-smelling vaginal discharge (may indicate infection)\n\n## Abdominal or Perineal Symptoms\n\n- Severe abdominal pain that doesn''t improve with pain medication\n- Abdominal swelling, redness, or warmth\n- Persistent pain at episiotomy or tear site\n- Inability to control bowel movements or gas after healing\n- Severe perineal pain worsening after initial improvement\n\n## Infection Signs\n\n- Fever of 100.4°F (38°C) or higher\n- Chills or night sweats\n- Foul-smelling vaginal discharge\n- Redness, swelling, warmth, or discharge from surgical incision\n- Breast redness, warmth, swelling, or pus\n\n## Cardiovascular Symptoms\n\n- Chest pain or pressure\n- Shortness of breath at rest or with minimal exertion\n- Rapid or irregular heartbeat\n- Leg pain, swelling, or warmth (may indicate blood clot)\n- Calf tenderness or difficulty walking\n\n## Breastfeeding Complications\n\n- Breast pain lasting more than the first week\n- Nipple cracks bleeding or showing signs of infection\n- Breast abscess—firm, painful lump with surrounding redness\n- Severe engorgement not relieved by cold packs and supportive bra\n- Concerns about milk supply with baby losing excessive weight\n\n## Urinary Symptoms\n\n- Inability to urinate within 6-8 hours postpartum\n- Painful urination lasting beyond the first week\n- Urinary tract infection signs: frequency, urgency, burning\n- Incontinence affecting daily activities after the first week\n\n## Mental Health Concerns\n\n- Persistent sadness or hopelessness lasting beyond 2 weeks\n- Inability to enjoy activities or bond with baby\n- Intrusive frightening thoughts about harming baby\n- Severe anxiety interfering with functioning\n- Panic attacks or difficulty breathing\n- Thoughts of harming yourself\n\n## Other Important Symptoms\n\n- Severe headache or vision changes\n- Unexplained aching in joints or muscles\n- Signs of allergy or medication reaction\n- Concerns about baby''s feeding or behavior\n- Any symptom causing you worry or concern\n\n## When to Seek Emergency Care\n\nGo to the nearest emergency room or call 911 for: severe chest pain, difficulty breathing, signs of stroke (facial drooping, arm weakness, speech difficulty), severe headache with vision changes, suicidal thoughts or thoughts of harming baby, uncontrolled bleeding, signs of severe infection with high fever and confusion.\n\n## Documentation\n\nKeep your postpartum discharge instructions accessible. They list your provider''s contact information and specify when to call versus when to seek emergency care. Don''t hesitate to contact your provider with questions; early evaluation prevents complications.',
  'checklist',
  'https://www.acog.org/womens-health/faqs/postpartum-care-faqs',
  0,
  12,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Returning to Exercise After Childbirth',
  'postpartum-exercise-return-activity',
  'Learn safe progressions for returning to physical activity after childbirth, considering your delivery type and recovery.',
  E'# Returning to Exercise After Childbirth\n\nPhysical activity supports postpartum recovery, mental health, and weight management. Safe, gradual progression allows your body to rebuild strength without compromising healing.\n\n## General Timeline Guidelines\n\nModerate exercise like walking can resume within days after uncomplicated vaginal delivery. More intense activity should wait until after your 6-week postpartum checkup. Cesarean delivery involves abdominal surgical incision; activity progression is slower. Complications like perineal tears or episiotomy may require modified timelines. Always obtain your provider''s clearance before beginning structured exercise programs.\n\n## First 2-4 Weeks\n\nFocus on gentle movement: short walks increasing gradually, pelvic floor awareness, and deep breathing. Avoid heavy lifting beyond your baby''s weight and repetitive bending. Gentle stretching maintains flexibility. If you feel faint, dizzy, or experience heavy bleeding during activity, rest and contact your provider. This period allows your body to stabilize and healing to progress.\n\n## Weeks 4-6\n\nGradually increase walking duration and intensity. Begin gentle postpartum-specific exercises targeting core and pelvic floor muscles. Avoid high-impact activities, heavy weights, and intense abdominal exercises like sit-ups. Listen to your body; some soreness is normal, but pain warrants stopping. Pelvic floor muscle strengthening (Kegels) can begin at any postpartum stage if done gently.\n\n## After 6-Week Clearance\n\nOnce cleared by your provider, gradually reintroduce structured exercise. Begin with low-impact activities like walking, swimming, cycling, or elliptical machines. Gradually increase intensity and duration over weeks. Strength training with light weights supports muscle rebuilding and bone health. High-impact activities (running, jumping, high-intensity classes) can progress as your pelvic floor strengthens.\n\n## Diastasis Recti and Core Recovery\n\nAbdominal muscle separation (diastasis recti) is common postpartum. Check for separation by lying on your back, placing fingers above your belly button, and gently lifting your head. A gap wider than 1-2 fingers indicates separation. Avoid exercises increasing intra-abdominal pressure—traditional crunches, planks, and double leg lifts. Work with a physical therapist specializing in postpartum recovery for appropriate exercises. As muscles reconnect, typically by 8 weeks, progressively challenging exercises become safe.\n\n## Pelvic Floor Considerations\n\nThe pelvic floor requires rebuilding. Signs of pelvic floor weakness include leaking urine with coughing, sneezing, or impact activities, and incomplete bladder emptying. Pelvic floor physical therapy addresses these concerns. Avoid high-impact activities until incontinence resolves, which prevents worsening weakness. Pelvic floor exercises (Kegels) strengthen supporting muscles; coordinate squeezing with breathing rather than sustained clenching.\n\n## Breastfeeding and Exercise\n\nExercise is compatible with breastfeeding. Vigorous exercise may slightly increase lactic acid in breast milk, but this doesn''t harm babies. Well-fitting sports bras reduce breast soreness. Hydration and nutrition increase with exercise intensity. Timing exercise after breastfeeding prevents breast fullness during activity.\n\n## Listening to Your Body\n\nReturn to pre-pregnancy activity gradually, potentially taking months. Increased bleeding, pain, or pelvic pressure warrants slowing progression. Fatigue is common; prioritize sleep and nutrition. Partner involvement in baby care creates exercise opportunities. Many gyms offer childcare, and stroller-based activities allow baby inclusion. Consistency matters more than intensity; regular moderate activity outweighs sporadic intense workouts.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.acog.org/womens-health/faqs/exercise-after-pregnancy',
  0,
  26,
  'published',
  false
);

-- Breastfeeding Resources
INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Getting Started with Breastfeeding: The First Week',
  'breastfeeding-first-week-getting-started',
  'Navigate the early breastfeeding journey with practical guidance for the critical first week of establishing nursing.',
  E'# Getting Started with Breastfeeding: The First Week\n\nThe first week of breastfeeding sets the foundation for long-term success. Understanding normal patterns and seeking early help with challenges dramatically improves outcomes.\n\n## First Hours After Birth\n\nMany babies naturally root and latch within the first hour after delivery. Immediate skin-to-skin contact between mother and baby supports this instinct. Babies are typically alert during this golden hour, before natural sleepiness sets in. Assist your baby to breast when signs of readiness appear: rooting (turning mouth toward breast), hand to mouth, increased alertness. If your baby doesn''t initiate feeding, gently guide them to breast for comfort and stimulation.\n\nMidwives and lactation consultants present during this early period can assess latch and provide guidance. Allow your baby to remain at the breast even if milk hasn''t appeared; this establishes bonding and stimulates milk production.\n\n## First 24-48 Hours: Colostrum Phase\n\nYour first milk, colostrum, is thick, concentrated, and perfectly suited to your newborn''s needs. Small amounts (5-10 milliliters per feeding) provide concentrated nutrition and protective antibodies. Frequent feeding stimulation is more important than volume during this phase. Babies should latch 8-12 times daily. Milk production begins in response to this stimulation.\n\nNewborns sleep heavily after delivery. Wake your baby for feedings if they''ve gone more than 3 hours without nursing. Gently undress them, stroke their feet, or position them skin-to-skin to encourage alertness.\n\n## Days 3-7: Milk Transitions\n\nAround day 3, milk transitions from colostrum to mature milk. Breasts may become noticeably fuller, warmer, and slightly uncomfortable—engorgement. This temporary fullness indicates milk production has increased. Cold compresses, supportive bras, and frequent feeding provide relief. Some engorgement is normal; severe engorgement interfering with latch requires attention from a lactation specialist.\n\nAs milk increases, babies feed more efficiently. Feeding sessions typically last 8-15 minutes per breast. Babies show contentment cues: relaxed body, slow rhythmic suckling, occasional swallowing sounds, hands unclenched. Allow your baby to finish the first breast before offering the second; this ensures adequate hind milk rich in fat and calories.\n\n## Recognizing Adequate Feeding\n\nDiaper output reliably indicates adequate milk intake. By day 3-4, expect at least 3 wet diapers and 3 stools daily; by day 5-7, expect 5-6 wet diapers and multiple stools. Stools transition from black meconium to greenish-brown to yellow-seedy consistency. Adequate output provides reassurance when milk volume feels uncertain. Jaundice screening and weight checks within the first week identify feeding concerns early.\n\n## Establishing Latch\n\nProper latch prevents nipple pain and ensures efficient milk transfer. Position your baby with mouth wide open, taking the entire areola into the mouth, not just the nipple. The baby''s lower lip rolls outward; the nose and chin touch the breast. This position allows the baby to compress the breast tissue effectively, drawing milk from milk ducts. Pain beyond mild discomfort indicates latch problems requiring lactation consultation.\n\n## Managing Common Early Concerns\n\nNipple soreness, engorgement, and difficulty expressing milk are common early concerns addressed through proper positioning, frequent feeding, and lactation support. Expecting some initial nipple discomfort is normal, but persistent pain indicates a fixable problem. Lactation consultants, available at hospitals and through private practice, provide hands-on guidance and assessment.\n\n## Sleep and Feeding Patterns\n\nNewborns require frequent feeding every 2-3 hours. Cluster feeding, when babies feed multiple times within a short period, is normal and increases milk supply. Expect variable feeding patterns; some days babies feed frequently, other days spacing increases. This variability is typical. Night feeding is part of early breastfeeding; newborns don''t distinguish day and night.\n\n## Support and Resources\n\nSeek lactation support before major problems develop. Hospital lactation consultants, midwives, and peer support groups provide guidance. Lactation consultants (International Board Certified, IBCLC) have specialized training and can assess complex situations. La Leche League offers peer support and evidence-based information. Breastfeeding hotlines provide accessible support.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care/breastfeeding-resources/',
  0,
  2,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Common Breastfeeding Challenges and Solutions',
  'breastfeeding-challenges-solutions',
  'Understand common breastfeeding difficulties and practical, evidence-based approaches to overcome them.',
  E'# Common Breastfeeding Challenges and Solutions\n\nMost breastfeeding challenges are temporary and solvable with appropriate support. Identifying problems early and seeking help prevents escalation.\n\n## Nipple Pain and Damage\n\nLanolin, hydrogel pads, and expressed milk soothe sore nipples. Proper latch prevents pain; a lactation consultant can assess positioning. Air drying between feedings supports healing. Avoid harsh soaps; water alone cleans the breast. Shield use during feeding protects damaged nipples while healing. Pain persisting beyond the first week indicates latch problems or infection requiring professional assessment.\n\n## Engorgement\n\nSwollen, hard, painful breasts occur as milk production increases. Frequent feeding every 2-3 hours provides relief. Cold compresses reduce inflammation and pain. Supportive bras, even worn overnight, provide comfort. Gentle hand expression or manual pumping initially softens the areola enough for the baby to latch. Severe engorgement lasting beyond a few days requires lactation support to ensure adequate drainage and prevent infection.\n\n## Plugged Ducts\n\nA firm, tender lump in breast tissue indicates a plugged duct where milk accumulates. Warm compresses before feeding promote drainage. Frequent feeding from the affected breast, with the baby''s chin pointing toward the lump, mechanically removes the blockage. Vary feeding positions to encourage drainage from different duct areas. Gentle massage above the lump during feeding facilitates movement. Plugged ducts resolve within 24-48 hours with frequent feeding; failure to resolve may indicate infection.\n\n## Mastitis and Breast Infection\n\nInfection presents with localized redness, warmth, swelling, and pain, often accompanied by fever and flu-like symptoms. Continued frequent feeding empties the breast and prevents abscess formation. Antibiotics treat bacterial infection. Supportive care includes pain management, hydration, and rest. Most cases resolve quickly with treatment. Breastfeeding continues safely during mastitis; antibiotics prescribed by your provider are safe during nursing.\n\n## Milk Supply Concerns\n\nAdequate milk supply is indicated by frequent wet and dirty diapers, audible swallowing, and weight gain. Apparent low supply often reflects normal variation or inaccurate perception. Frequent feeding stimulates production; restriction causes supply decline. Ensuring proper latch and frequent nursing (at least 8-12 times daily) maintain adequate supply. Medications, alcohol, and certain herbs may reduce supply. Stress and sleep deprivation impact production; support and rest help. If concern persists, a lactation consultant can assess milk transfer effectiveness and recommend strategies.\n\n## Oversupply\n\nExcessive milk causes rapid let-down, fast flow, and baby discomfort. Block feeding—offering only one breast per 2-3 hour period—reduces supply without eliminating it. Recline positioning allows babies to pace feeding despite fast flow. Expressing just enough to relieve pressure prevents signaling increased production. Ice packs reduce inflammation. Oversupply gradually resolves as supply stabilizes to meet demand, typically after several weeks.\n\n## Latch and Positioning Difficulties\n\nLatch problems prevent effective milk transfer and cause pain. Signs include clicking sounds, visible nipple damage, and baby''s weight plateau. A lactation consultant provides hands-on assessment and positioning coaching. Football hold, cradle hold, and side-lying positions suit different body types and situations. Experiment to find comfortable positions. Nipple shields ease transition as latch improves.\n\n## Reluctant Feeders\n\nSome babies show disinterest in breastfeeding despite adequate milk. Skin-to-skin contact without pressure to feed builds connection. Nursing in a calm, quiet environment reduces distractions. Supplementary nursing systems allow feeding breast milk while maintaining breastfeeding. Patience and consistent offering, without forcing, often resolves reluctance.\n\n## Thrush and Yeast Infections\n\nWhite patches inside baby''s mouth or mother''s nipple pain with burning sensation indicate yeast overgrowth. Antifungal treatment prescribed by your provider addresses both mother and baby simultaneously. Wash hands after diaper changes, sterilize pacifiers, and change nursing pads frequently to reduce fungal transmission. Treatment continues until symptoms resolve plus additional time to prevent recurrence.',
  'article',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care/breastfeeding-resources/',
  0,
  52,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Understanding Your Milk Supply',
  'understanding-milk-supply-breastfeeding',
  'Learn how milk supply works, how to assess adequacy, and strategies to maintain healthy production.',
  E'# Understanding Your Milk Supply\n\nMilk supply directly responds to demand. Understanding this fundamental principle helps you manage production confidently and recognize actual problems.\n\n## How Milk Supply Works\n\nMilk production begins when milk ducts receive signals from the hormone prolactin, released in response to breast emptying. The more frequently your breasts empty, the more prolactin is produced, and the more milk you produce. This supply-demand relationship continues throughout lactation. Early frequent feeding stimulates establishing adequate production. As lactation continues, milk production becomes more efficient; frequency matters less than ensuring regular complete breast drainage.\n\nLocal factors within the breast also regulate production. Milk contains a protein, feedback inhibitor of lactation (FIL), that slows production when present. Frequent emptying removes FIL, allowing continued production. Infrequent emptying allows FIL accumulation, signaling reduced production. This elegant system naturally adjusts supply to match your baby''s needs.\n\n## Assessing Milk Supply\n\nThe most reliable indicator of adequate supply is baby''s output and growth. Expect 5-6 wet diapers and multiple yellow, seedy stools daily by the second week. Weight gain of 3-7 ounces weekly indicates adequate milk intake. Monthly growth at regular intervals (check-ups) confirms sustained adequate supply.\n\nDo not rely on subjective feelings of fullness; many mothers with abundant milk never feel full. Do not measure milk by pumped quantities; pumps extract less milk than babies. Do not count feeding frequency alone; some babies efficiently transfer milk in short sessions while others need longer feeds. Objective indicators—diaper output and growth—accurately assess supply.\n\n## Establishing Supply in Early Weeks\n\nFrequent feeding 8-12 times daily, starting within the first hour after birth, establishes strong production. Night feeding matters; prolactin levels are highest during night hours. Incomplete breast draining or extended gaps between feedings reduce supply, particularly in the first 2-3 months. Ensuring proper latch allows efficient milk transfer, preventing the need for excessive feeding sessions while maintaining strong supply signals.\n\n## Common Supply Concerns\n\nPerceived low supply often reflects normal supply variation or inefficient milk transfer from latch problems. Before assuming low supply, have a lactation consultant observe feeding and assess latch. Once latch is optimized, most supply concerns resolve.\n\nActual low supply is rare but can result from delayed initiation of feeding, infrequent feeding, inadequate latch, scheduled feeding patterns, or certain medications. Addressing the underlying cause—frequent feeding, latch correction, or medication adjustment—usually resolves low supply.\n\n## Strategies to Support Supply\n\nFrequent feeding remains the most important strategy. Feeding at least 8 times daily for the first month, then continuing regular feeding, maintains adequate production. Skin-to-skin contact promotes feeding frequency and hormone production. Adequate maternal nutrition, hydration, and sleep support production; malnutrition or severe sleep deprivation may impact supply. Stress reduces prolactin; reducing stress and accepting help improve production.\n\nSome substances affect milk supply. Alcohol, particularly in excessive amounts, may reduce supply. Certain medications affect production; discuss any new medications with your provider. Hormonal contraceptives containing estrogen reduce supply; progesterone-only methods are safer. Sage, peppermint, and other herbs may reduce supply; maintain herbal intake awareness. Conversely, fenugreek and blessed thistle may support supply when combined with frequent feeding.\n\n## Oversupply Management\n\nExcessive production, less common than perceived low supply, creates discomfort and rapid feeding. Block feeding—nursing from one breast per feeding cycle—reduces supply without eliminating it. Gradually return to both breasts as supply adjusts. Ice packs provide comfort. Oversupply typically resolves within weeks as supply naturally regulates to match demand.\n\n## Expressing and Storing Milk\n\nManual expression or pumping adds production only if milk drainage is incomplete through nursing. Unnecessary expression stimulates excess production. Once supply is established and baby is nursing well, expressing need not occur. If away from baby, expressing maintains supply and provides milk for use. Storage guidelines: room temperature 4 hours, refrigerator 4 days, freezer 6-12 months depending on appliance.',
  'article',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care/breastfeeding-resources/',
  0,
  52,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'Pumping and Storing Breast Milk Safely',
  'pumping-storing-breast-milk-guidelines',
  'Learn safe practices for expressing, storing, and handling breast milk to maintain nutritional value and prevent contamination.',
  E'# Pumping and Storing Breast Milk Safely\n\nMany parents express milk for various reasons. Proper technique and storage ensure milk maintains safety and nutritional quality.\n\n## Manual Expression Versus Pumping\n\nManual expression involves hand compression and massage to extract milk. This technique requires no equipment and provides milk for immediate use or temporary storage. Learning proper hand expression early allows flexibility if pumping equipment is unavailable.\n\nBreast pumps—manual, electric, or hospital-grade—provide hands-free expression and higher volume in less time than manual expression. Single pumps extract from one breast; double pumps from both simultaneously, reducing pumping time. Hospital-grade pumps provide the most suction strength. Renting hospital-grade pumps is cost-effective for short-term use; purchase is appropriate for long-term pumping.\n\n## Pumping Technique and Frequency\n\nBegin pumping after nursing once milk supply is established, typically around 2-4 weeks postpartum. Expressing before complete supply establishment may overstimulate production. Pumping after nursing ensures baby receives milk first, maintaining adequate direct nursing. Pumping while baby naps or sleeps provides convenient time.\n\nFrequency depends on needs. For occasional bottle use, pumping once or twice daily maintains supply without excessive production. Return-to-work schedules typically involve pumping every 3-4 hours while away from baby. More frequent pumping increases supply; less frequent decreases it. Duration typically ranges 15-20 minutes until milk flow slows; longer pumping beyond milk flow doesn''t increase output but may cause discomfort.\n\n## Storage Guidelines\n\nStored breast milk remains safe following strict guidelines:\n\nRoom temperature (68-72°F): 4 hours\nInsulated cooler with ice packs: 24 hours\nRefrigerator (35-38°F): 4 days (store in back, not door)\nFreezer (0°F or lower): 6 months standard freezer, 12 months deep freezer\n\nUse oldest milk first. Label milk with date expressed. Thaw frozen milk under warm running water or in warm water bath; never use microwave, which creates hot spots. Thawed milk lasts 24 hours refrigerated. Never refreeze thawed milk.\n\n## Containers and Labeling\n\nUse food-grade containers: sterile glass bottles, BPA-free plastic bottles, or storage bags designed for breast milk. Storage bags take minimal space and are convenient for freezing. Avoid regular plastic bags, which may leak. Clean containers with hot soapy water or sterilize before use if not sterile. Allow to air dry completely.\n\nLabel each container with date and time expressed and baby''s name if stored in a shared space (like childcare). Some parents also note volume, though this isn''t necessary.\n\n## Hygiene and Contamination Prevention\n\nWash hands before expressing. Clean pump parts and bottles with hot soapy water immediately after use; dry thoroughly. Sterilize equipment daily by boiling, steam sterilizing, or using sterilizing tablets. Do not allow milk residue to dry; clean promptly.\n\nBreast milk contains antibodies protecting baby from infection. Even if contaminated, breast milk rarely causes illness; babies have protective mechanisms. However, follow guidelines to maintain optimal safety.\n\n## Combining Milk from Multiple Expressions\n\nMilk from different pumping sessions can be combined if freshly expressed milk is cooled to same temperature as previously stored milk before combining. This prevents warming previously cold milk. Combine in a single container, label with earliest expression time, and follow the earliest expiration date.\n\n## Storage Changes and Layer Separation\n\nFat naturally separates from water in stored milk; shaking or gently swirling (not vigorous mixing) redistributes fat. The cream layer is desirable; do not discard it. Appearance or smell changes may indicate spoilage; when uncertain, discard. Frozen milk may appear discolored due to oxidation; this is normal if smell is acceptable.\n\n## Transportation and Use\n\nInsulated coolers with ice packs maintain cold temperatures during transport. Milk can remain in cooler 24 hours with appropriate ice. Upon arrival at destination, refrigerate immediately. Warm milk under warm running water or in warm water bath before offering. Never warm in microwave. Use within guidelines once thawed.\n\n## Returning to Work\n\nPlan pumping schedule matching baby''s feeding pattern. Coordinate with childcare provider regarding milk storage at their facility. Transport supplies include pump, collection bottles, storage bags, and cooling containers. Many employers provide private spaces for pumping; federal law (FLSA) requires reasonable break time and private space, though enforcement varies. Coordinate with employer and childcare to establish sustainable routine.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.cdc.gov/breastfeeding/recommendations/storage-handling.html',
  0,
  104,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium) VALUES
(
  'When and How to Introduce a Bottle',
  'introducing-bottle-to-breastfeeding-baby',
  'Learn optimal timing and techniques for introducing bottles while maintaining successful breastfeeding.',
  E'# When and How to Introduce a Bottle\n\nMany breastfeeding families introduce bottles to provide flexibility and allow caregivers to feed expressed milk. Proper timing and technique support continued direct breastfeeding while enabling bottle feeding.\n\n## Optimal Timing for Bottle Introduction\n\nIntroduce bottles after breastfeeding is well established, typically around 3-4 weeks postpartum. By this age, babies have developed consistent latch and suckling patterns, and milk supply has stabilized. Introducing bottles too early may cause confusion, reducing direct nursing and milk supply. Introducing too late may lead to bottle refusal. Some babies readily accept bottles at any age; others require specific timing to transition successfully.\n\nWait to introduce bottles until after breastfeeding is established: baby is gaining weight appropriately, nursing painlessly, and demonstrating normal milk transfer with adequate wet and dirty diapers.\n\n## Bottle Types and Teats\n\nSlow-flow teats with wide bases designed to mimic breast anatomy support smooth transition. Standard bottle teats may cause faster flow, leading to preference if baby must work less hard to receive milk. Anti-colic bottles reduce air ingestion. Some babies prefer specific bottle shapes; trying multiple types helps identify preferences.\n\nWarm milk to approximately body temperature (98.6°F). Room temperature milk is acceptable; cold milk is not recommended as it may upset baby''s stomach.\n\n## Feeding Technique\n\nAllow baby to pace feeding, taking breaks and controlling flow—mimicking breast feeding. Hold baby semi-upright, supporting their head; never prop bottles. Gently touch teats to baby''s lips and allow them to open mouth and accept the teat. When baby is ready, they latch and drink. Allow pauses between suckling bursts; this paced feeding prevents overfeeding and maintains baby''s natural rhythm.\n\nBabies who bottle feed quickly without pausing may be overfed. Slow paced feeding by removing bottle frequently and allowing rest prevents excess intake and reduces fussiness from overfeeding.\n\n## Introducing the First Bottle\n\nHave someone other than mother offer the first bottle, as baby associates mother with breastfeeding and may be confused by bottle in mother''s hands. A partner or trusted caregiver offering the bottle in a calm, positive manner often increases acceptance. Remain nearby but out of sight; baby may smell milk and seek the breast instead.\n\nOffer bottle when baby is calm and mildly hungry, not famished or overtired. Frustrated hungry babies refuse bottles. Offer when you have time to be patient; rushed feeding adds stress to baby and caregiver.\n\nMay require several attempts for acceptance. Offer bottle every few days; repeated exposure normalizes the experience. Some babies readily accept; others require weeks of exposure. Patience is essential.\n\n## Frequency and Maintaining Supply\n\nBottle feeding one or two times weekly maintains milk supply while providing caregiving flexibility. Bottle feeding more frequently requires expressing to maintain supply; express when baby would have nursed. This prevents supply decline and engorgement.\n\nReturn-to-work situations require planning to maintain supply. Express during work hours, refrigerate or freeze, and use stored milk in bottles at home. Continue nursing morning, evening, and nights to maintain direct breastfeeding and supply stimulation.\n\n## Combination Feeding (Breast and Bottle)\n\nMany families successfully combine breastfeeding and bottle feeding. Some babies prefer breast; some prefer bottle; many show no preference. Variation in feeding method does not impact bonding. Breastfeeding offers nutritional benefits and maternal-infant closeness; bottles provide flexibility. Both are valuable.\n\nMaintain some direct breastfeeding for milk supply stimulation and immune benefits. Complete transition to bottle feeding, while possible, requires careful planning to avoid engorgement and supply decline. If contemplating weaning to bottles exclusively, phase out breastfeeding gradually (over weeks to months) rather than suddenly.\n\n## Addressing Bottle Refusal\n\nSome exclusively breastfed babies refuse bottles. Continued exposure without pressure gradually normalizes bottles. Try different bottle types, teats, temperatures, and holding positions. Feed when calm and mildly hungry. Have caregiver other than mother offer bottle. Patience typically results in eventual acceptance. If refusal persists, cup feeding offers an alternative method for bottle-refusers to receive expressed milk.\n\n## Preventing Nipple Confusion\n\nThe term ''nipple confusion'' is outdated; babies do not become confused between breasts and bottles. Some babies show feeding preference, nursing less effectively after bottle feeding if the bottle teat requires less effort. Ensure proper breastfeeding latch and positioning; ineffective latch may decrease interest in direct nursing. Maintain regular breastfeeding; babies nursing efficiently continue preferring the breast.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care/breastfeeding-resources/',
  2,
  26,
  'published',
  false
);
-- NUTRITION & DIET RESOURCES
INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Introducing Solid Foods: Signs of Readiness',
  'introducing-solid-foods-signs-readiness',
  'Learn the developmental milestones and physical signs that indicate your baby is ready to begin solids.',
  E'# Introducing Solid Foods: Signs of Readiness\n\nStarting solid foods is a significant developmental milestone that typically occurs around 6 months of age, though readiness varies among infants. The American Academy of Pediatrics emphasizes that developmental readiness is more important than chronological age when determining the right time to introduce solids.\n\n## Key Signs of Readiness\n\nBabies display several developmental indicators suggesting they are physiologically prepared for solid foods. These include the ability to sit upright with minimal support, loss of the tongue-thrust reflex (which naturally pushes food out of the mouth), and the emergence of the raking grasp reflex, allowing babies to pick up and manipulate objects independently.\n\nAdditional signs of readiness involve your baby showing interest in food by watching others eat, reaching for utensils or food items, and opening their mouth when a spoon approaches. Many babies also demonstrate increased hunger that cannot be satisfied by breast milk or formula alone, though this alone should not drive the decision to introduce solids.\n\n## Physical Development Milestones\n\nRolling from back to front and maintaining head control while seated are critical prerequisites for safe feeding. Your baby should be able to stabilize their head without significant support from caregivers. This coordination prevents aspiration and allows proper swallowing mechanics during the introduction of thicker foods.\n\nThe reduction or disappearance of the extrusion reflex is particularly important. This reflex, which is protective during the early months, prevents young infants from handling thicker textures safely. When this reflex diminishes, babies can manage pureed foods more effectively.\n\n## Starting the Process\n\nWhen readiness is confirmed, introduce one iron-fortified infant cereal at a time, mixing it with breast milk or formula to achieve a thin, soupy consistency. Offer small amounts on a soft-tipped spoon during calm, interactive feeding sessions. This allows observation of potential allergic reactions and ensures a positive feeding experience.\n\nWatch for signs of choking or gagging, and understand that gagging is a protective reflex that is normal and different from actual choking. Wait 3-5 days before introducing a new food to identify any adverse reactions. This gradual approach helps establish healthy eating patterns while protecting your infant from potential risks.\n\nParental observation and responsiveness to your baby''s developmental cues create the foundation for successful feeding transitions and lifelong healthy relationships with food.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  17,
  30,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Iron-Rich Foods for Infants and Toddlers',
  'iron-rich-foods-infants-toddlers',
  'Discover iron-rich food options and feeding strategies to prevent anemia and support healthy development.',
  E'# Iron-Rich Foods for Infants and Toddlers\n\nIron is a critical micronutrient for infant and toddler development, supporting cognitive function, immune competence, and the production of hemoglobin for oxygen transport. Breast milk and formula provide adequate iron for the first months of life, but supplementation through solid foods becomes essential as babies grow.\n\n## Iron Fortification and Natural Sources\n\nInfant cereals fortified with iron serve as a primary source when solids are introduced around 6 months. Single-grain cereals like iron-fortified rice, oat, and barley cereals deliver bioavailable iron in forms designed for developing digestive systems. As your baby progresses to mixed cereals, varied iron sources become available.\n\nMeat-based foods provide highly bioavailable heme iron, which is absorbed more efficiently than non-heme iron from plant sources. Pureed beef, poultry, and pork can be introduced starting around 8 months. These foods should be prepared without added salt or seasonings initially, allowing infants to become familiar with the natural flavors while building tolerance for diverse protein sources.\n\n## Plant-Based Iron Options\n\nFortified infant foods, including vegetable purees and combination meals, contribute to total iron intake. Beans and lentils, introduced as tolerated, provide non-heme iron and plant-based protein. While non-heme iron absorption is lower, pairing these foods with vitamin C sources significantly enhances bioavailability.\n\nToddlers can begin enjoying finely minced or ground meats, making iron accessibility through family meals increasingly practical. Eggs, another iron source, can be introduced around 8-9 months in modified forms and later as whole foods as the toddler develops.\n\n## Optimizing Iron Absorption\n\nVitamin C consumption enhances non-heme iron absorption substantially. Including fruits and vegetables like sweet potato, squash, and later citrus options alongside iron-rich meals improves nutritional benefit. Tea and coffee, which inhibit iron absorption, should be avoided entirely during early childhood.\n\nResponsive feeding practices that respect your child''s appetite cues while offering variety support adequate iron intake without forcing consumption. Regular monitoring through growth curves and developmental assessments provides reassurance that nutritional needs are being met effectively throughout the transition to family foods.',
  'article',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  26,
  156,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Common Food Allergens: When and How to Introduce',
  'common-food-allergens-introduction',
  'Evidence-based guidance on introducing major allergens early to reduce allergic disease risk.',
  E'# Common Food Allergens: When and How to Introduce\n\nRecent research from the American Academy of Pediatrics and international allergy organizations has fundamentally shifted recommendations regarding allergen introduction. Rather than delaying allergenic foods, current evidence supports introducing major allergens relatively early, potentially reducing the risk of developing food allergies and other atopic conditions.\n\n## The Major Allergens\n\nThe top eight food allergens account for the majority of allergic reactions and include peanuts, tree nuts, milk, eggs, fish, shellfish, wheat, and soy. Research demonstrates that early, repeated exposure to these allergens, rather than avoidance, may promote oral tolerance development and reduce sensitization risk.\n\nIntroduction should occur after basic solids have been established and while monitoring is possible. Peanut-containing foods, for example, have been shown in landmark studies to reduce peanut allergy development when introduced by 11 months in infants without prior reactions. Products like peanut-based infant foods or smooth peanut butter mixed with infant cereal provide appropriate introductions.\n\n## Introduction Strategy\n\nIntroduce one new allergen at a time in small quantities, preferably during daytime hours when medical support is most accessible. Offer approximately 1/4 to 1/2 teaspoon initially and watch for local or systemic reactions over the following hours. If tolerated, continue offering that food regularly over subsequent weeks to promote tolerance development.\n\nTree nuts can be introduced as finely ground nut flours mixed into appropriate foods, or as smooth, thin nut butters in minimal quantities. Eggs, which are commonly used in infant foods, can be introduced as soft-cooked yolk initially, progressing to whole eggs as tolerated. Fish and shellfish should be offered as finely minced or pureed preparations.\n\n## Individual Risk Considerations\n\nInfants with established food allergies, moderate-to-severe eczema, or family histories of multiple allergies may warrant supervised introduction protocols or allergy specialist consultation. For these higher-risk infants, the timing and method of introduction may differ from general recommendations.\n\nRegular allergen exposure after successful introduction maintains and strengthens oral tolerance. Avoiding foods that have been successfully introduced may actually increase allergy risk, making consistent inclusion in the diet important. Document any reactions carefully and discuss with your pediatrician to establish safe introduction patterns tailored to your infant''s individual risk profile.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  17,
  52,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Healthy Eating Habits for Toddlers',
  'healthy-eating-habits-toddlers',
  'Build positive feeding practices and food preferences during the critical toddler nutrition years.',
  E'# Healthy Eating Habits for Toddlers\n\nThe toddler years represent a crucial window for establishing dietary patterns and food preferences that track into childhood and adulthood. Responsive feeding practices that honor satiety cues while exposing children to varied, nutritious foods create the foundation for lifetime healthy eating behaviors.\n\n## Division of Responsibility\n\nFeeding experts recommend a clear division of responsibility between caregiver and child. Parents determine what foods are offered, when feeding occurs, and the eating environment. Toddlers decide whether to eat and how much to consume from the foods provided. This approach respects developing autonomy while guiding nutritional intake.\n\nOffers should include at least one food that the toddler is likely to accept, even if other foods on the table are unfamiliar. Repeated exposure to new foods, without pressure, gradually builds acceptance and willingness to try novel options. Many toddlers require 10-15 exposures to a new food before accepting it.\n\n## Creating Positive Mealtime Experiences\n\nEating together as a family, when possible, models healthy food relationships and normalizes varied diets. Conversation, enjoyment, and connection around meals establish eating as a social experience rather than a battleground. Toddlers learn through observation and imitation, adopting attitudes toward food from family members.\n\nOffer foods in forms that support independence and skill development. Soft-textured pieces that toddlers can self-feed build confidence and fine motor skills. Involving toddlers in food selection, preparation, and cleanup when age-appropriate increases investment in eating the foods prepared.\n\n## Nutrient-Dense Food Selection\n\nToddlers require nutrient-dense foods rather than calorie-dense options, as their stomach capacity limits total intake. Whole grains, fruits, vegetables, proteins, and dairy products provide essential nutrients for rapid growth and development. While toddlers are often selective eaters, continued exposure to diverse foods maintains access to varied nutrient sources.\n\nLimiting sugar-sweetened beverages and sugary snacks protects dental health and prevents displacement of nutrient-dense foods. Water and milk remain appropriate beverages. Dairy products, if tolerated, provide calcium and vitamin D for bone development.\n\n## Managing Developmental Eating Changes\n\nToddler appetite and intake often fluctuate with growth patterns and developmental changes. Periods of decreased appetite alternate with spurts of increased consumption. This variability is normal and does not indicate inadequate nutrition when energy distribution is viewed over days rather than individual meals.\n\nPressuring toddlers to eat beyond satiety signals, praising clean plates, or using food as reward can disrupt natural hunger-satiety regulation. These practices increase risk for overweight and disconnection from internal nutritional cues. Trusting toddler appetite while providing consistent, nutritious options supports healthy growth and eating relationships.',
  'article',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  52,
  260,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Vitamin D and Other Essential Supplements for Babies',
  'vitamin-d-essential-supplements-babies',
  'Comprehensive overview of vitamin D, iron, and other supplements recommended during infancy.',
  E'# Vitamin D and Other Essential Supplements for Babies\n\nWhile breast milk and formula provide most essential nutrients, certain supplements are recommended to prevent deficiency diseases and support optimal development. Understanding which supplements are necessary and when to introduce them helps ensure comprehensive nutritional support.\n\n## Vitamin D Supplementation\n\nVitamin D is critical for calcium absorption, bone development, and immune function. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends that all infants receive 400 IU of vitamin D daily, beginning shortly after birth, regardless of feeding method. This recommendation applies because human milk contains minimal vitamin D, and formula may not contain sufficient quantities despite fortification.\n\nVitamin D supplements are available as liquid drops designed for infants, making administration straightforward. Most supplements contain 400 IU per recommended dose. Direct sunlight exposure, while important for vitamin D synthesis, is not recommended as a sole source during infancy due to skin cancer risks and variable effectiveness based on geography and season.\n\n## Iron Supplementation\n\nIron needs increase substantially around 6 months as maternal iron stores deplete. Exclusively breast-fed babies benefit from iron-fortified infant cereals and iron-rich foods introduced with solids. Formula-fed infants receive iron from fortified infant formula. By 12 months, all infants should receive iron from either fortified foods or supplements if dietary sources are insufficient.\n\nIron supplementation may be recommended if dietary intake is inadequate, particularly for breast-fed infants whose mothers did not have optimal iron stores. Liquid iron supplements are available for infants, though they may cause temporary tooth staining. Proper administration away from meals and teeth promotes safety and effectiveness.\n\n## Fluoride Considerations\n\nFluoride supplementation is recommended in areas where water is not fluoridated, though the specific dose depends on age and water fluoride content. Beginning around 6 months, infants in non-fluoridated areas may benefit from fluoride supplements, which support tooth enamel development and cavity prevention.\n\nDiscuss fluoride recommendations with your pediatrician, who can determine whether supplementation is appropriate based on local water fluoridation. Excessive fluoride intake during tooth development can cause fluorosis, making appropriate dosing important.\n\n## Additional Considerations\n\nWhile vitamin A, C, and other nutrients are essential, they are adequately provided through breast milk or formula when infants are fed appropriately. Probiotics and other supplements lack sufficient evidence for routine recommendation, though specific products may be beneficial in particular situations as determined by your pediatrician.\n\nMultivitamins are generally unnecessary if your infant is fed breast milk or formula and receives recommended single-nutrient supplements. Always inform your pediatrician of any supplements given to ensure coordinated care and prevent excessive intake of any single nutrient.',
  'article',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  0,
  52,
  'published',
  false
);

-- SLEEP RESOURCES
INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Safe Sleep Guidelines for Newborns',
  'safe-sleep-guidelines-newborns',
  'Evidence-based recommendations for reducing SIDS risk and creating a safe sleep environment.',
  E'# Safe Sleep Guidelines for Newborns\n\nSudden Infant Death Syndrome (SIDS) remains a leading cause of death in infants between 1 month and 1 year. The American Academy of Pediatrics has established comprehensive evidence-based guidelines that, when implemented consistently, reduce SIDS risk by approximately 80%.\n\n## Sleep Surface Requirements\n\nNewborns should sleep on a firm, flat sleep surface such as a crib, bassinet, portable playard, or play yard that meets safety standards. This surface should be in your room, close to your bed, ideally for at least the first six months and optimally through the first year. Room-sharing without bed-sharing reduces the risk of SIDS and other sleep-related deaths.\n\nThe sleep surface must be completely bare—free of pillows, blankets, bumper pads, and soft objects that could obstruct breathing or cause entrapment. Crib sheets should be fitted and snug, designed specifically for the crib dimensions. Some families use sleep sacks or wearable blankets as safe alternatives to loose bedding that maintain comfort while avoiding suffocation risks.\n\n## Sleep Position and Environment\n\nAlways place your baby on their back for all sleep periods, including naps and nighttime sleep. This position remains protective throughout infancy. While tummy time during waking hours is important for development, sleep time should always begin with the back position.\n\nKeep the room at a comfortable temperature to prevent overheating, which is associated with increased SIDS risk. Room temperature should typically allow for light clothing without additional blankets. Watch for signs of overheating such as sweating, damp hair, or rapid breathing when your infant sleeps.\n\n## Feeding and Pacifier Use\n\nBoth breast feeding and formula feeding provide SIDS protection, with exclusive breast feeding offering slightly greater risk reduction. Feeding should be responsive to infant hunger cues rather than scheduled, optimizing nutrition while building early feeding relationships.\n\nIntroduction of a pacifier at nap time and bedtime, after breast feeding is established in exclusively breast-fed infants (typically around one month), offers additional SIDS protection. For formula-fed infants, pacifier introduction can occur from birth. The pacifier need not be actively kept in the mouth throughout sleep—offering it at sleep onset provides the protective benefit.\n\n## Avoiding Risk Factors\n\nPrenatal exposure to smoke, alcohol, and drug use increases SIDS risk substantially. Avoidance of these substances during pregnancy and the postpartum period is essential. Similarly, smoke, alcohol, and drug exposure in the infant''s environment should be completely eliminated.\n\nAvoid commercial devices marketed as SIDS reducers that lack scientific evidence, including bed-sharing sleepers, inclined sleepers, and wedges. Keep sleeping infants away from household smoke, alcohol vapor, and illicit drug exposure. Vaccination, particularly against influenza and pertussis, provides additional protection. Consistent implementation of these recommendations dramatically reduces your newborn''s SIDS risk.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  0,
  26,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Understanding Newborn Sleep Patterns',
  'understanding-newborn-sleep-patterns',
  'Learn about typical newborn sleep, wake-sleep cycles, and how to respond to your baby''s needs.',
  E'# Understanding Newborn Sleep Patterns\n\nNewborn sleep patterns mystify many new parents, as babies do not follow adult sleep schedules or conventions. Understanding the biological basis for newborn sleep behavior helps parents respond appropriately to infant needs and establish realistic expectations during the early weeks.\n\n## Typical Newborn Sleep Duration and Distribution\n\nNewborns sleep 16-17 hours per 24-hour period on average, though significant individual variation exists. Rather than consolidating sleep into nighttime periods, newborns distribute sleep across multiple brief episodes throughout the day and night. This polyphasic sleep pattern reflects their neurological development and feeding needs rather than indicating a problem.\n\nNewborns typically sleep 30 minutes to 2 hours before waking to feed, with the longest consolidated sleep period rarely exceeding 3-4 hours even in older newborns. Rapid eye movement (REM) sleep comprises approximately 50% of newborn sleep compared to 20% in adults, supporting brain development and neurological organization during this critical period.\n\n## Developmental Sleep Architecture\n\nNewborn sleep cycles last approximately 50-60 minutes, significantly shorter than the 90-minute sleep cycles of older children and adults. Each cycle progresses through non-REM sleep stages before reaching REM sleep. The brevity of these cycles means newborns transition between sleep states and wake periods frequently, sometimes appearing to waken abruptly.\n\nNewborns lack clear circadian rhythm consolidation, meaning they do not yet differentiate day from night. Gradual establishment of day-night differentiation occurs over weeks and months through exposure to light-dark cycles and feeding schedules, but this process is naturally slower during early infancy.\n\n## Responding to Newborn Sleep Needs\n\nNewborn sleep should be approached with flexibility and responsiveness rather than rigid scheduling. Feeding on cue rather than scheduled intervals better supports both infant nutrition and natural sleep-wake patterns. Watching for tired cues—such as eye rubbing, yawning, or decreased responsiveness—and facilitating sleep during these windows often proves more effective than clock-based sleep routines.\n\nWhile newborns sleep frequently, they also require periodic wakefulness for feeding, diaper changes, and interaction. Some waking periods represent normal sleep architecture rather than problems requiring intervention. Distinguishing between normal brief arousals and true waking periods that require parental response develops with experience.\n\n## Environmental Optimization\n\nWhile newborns are resilient sleepers, certain environmental factors support better sleep quality. Consistent room temperature, minimal bright light (except during daytime hours), and moderate noise levels create conditions conducive to sleep. Many newborns sleep better with white noise or consistent background sounds that mask environmental variations.\n\nKeeping your newborn close during sleep enables responsive attention to subtle hunger cues and prevents overheating from excessive swaddling or blankets. Swaddling, when done safely with the hips free to move, helps some newborns feel secure, though it should be transitioned away as the baby begins to show signs of rolling.',
  'article',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  0,
  12,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Sleep Training Methods: An Evidence-Based Overview',
  'sleep-training-methods-overview',
  'Comparison of sleep training approaches, effectiveness data, and guidance for implementation.',
  E'# Sleep Training Methods: An Evidence-Based Overview\n\nSleep training encompasses various behavioral strategies designed to help older infants and toddlers learn to initiate and maintain sleep independently. While sleep training is optional and some families choose not to implement these methods, evidence-based approaches can effectively address problematic sleep patterns when desired.\n\n## Graduated Extinction (Cry It Out)\n\nGradual extinction involves allowing the infant to fall asleep independently without parental contact, while checking periodically to ensure safety. Parents establish intervals (e.g., checking at 5 minutes, 10 minutes, 15 minutes) and maintain consistent intervals across nights, gradually lengthening checks as the infant learns to self-soothe.\n\nResearch demonstrates effectiveness, with most infants showing improved sleep within 3-7 nights. This method produces faster results than gentler approaches but generates significant parental stress and requires strong commitment to consistency. The term ''cry it out'' proves misleading, as gentle checking and reassurance occur regularly rather than complete ignoring.\n\n## Fading Methods (Camping Out)\n\nParent-present methods involve gradually reducing parental physical presence and assistance. A parent might begin by sitting beside the crib, gradually moving the chair further away across nights or weeks, eventually leaving the room. This approach maintains parental involvement and allows earlier intervention if the infant becomes distressed.\n\nFading methods proceed slowly, often requiring 2-4 weeks or longer to achieve independent sleep. While less stressful for parents, the process demands consistent effort and patience. Some families find the gradual nature more compatible with their parenting philosophy.\n\n## Scheduled Awakening\n\nThis approach involves waking the infant intentionally just before typical spontaneous waking times, then using soothing methods to return them to sleep. Over nights or weeks, scheduled awakenings prevent the arousal-to-crying pattern. Parents essentially ''schedule'' the disruption rather than responding reactively.\n\nThis method works best for infants with predictable waking patterns and produces slower but potentially less stressful change. Success depends on accurate pattern identification and commitment to the schedule.\n\n## Considerations for Implementation\n\nSleep training is most effective after 4-6 months of age when infants are developmentally capable of extending sleep periods and learning behavioral patterns. Introducing training earlier, though not harmful, typically proves ineffective as the infant still requires frequent night feeding.\n\nParental readiness, family values, and infant temperament should guide method selection. Infants with high-need temperaments may struggle more with extinction methods. Families uncomfortable with any crying or infant distress should choose gentler approaches, even if they require longer implementation periods.\n\n## Important Cautions\n\nSleep training should never begin during periods of significant stress, illness, developmental transitions (teething, developmental leaps), or major life changes. The inconsistency that results from these circumstances undermines success and may increase behavioral difficulty. Timing implementation for stable periods optimizes outcomes.',
  'article',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  16,
  52,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Establishing a Bedtime Routine',
  'establishing-bedtime-routine',
  'Create consistent, calming routines that signal sleep time and improve sleep quality and duration.',
  E'# Establishing a Bedtime Routine\n\nConsistent bedtime routines provide neurobiological and psychological benefits that extend beyond simply improving sleep behavior. Predictable pre-sleep activities help regulate the circadian system, reduce physiological arousal, and create emotional security that facilitates falling asleep and staying asleep throughout the night.\n\n## Components of Effective Routines\n\nSuccessful bedtime routines typically last 30-60 minutes and involve 3-4 calming activities that progressively reduce stimulation and prepare the body for sleep. A typical sequence might include bath time, followed by putting on pajamas, reading stories, singing, and soothing physical touch like gentle rocking or back rubbing.\n\nThe specific activities matter less than consistency and the progression toward decreasing stimulation. Bathing provides sensory input and can be soothing or overstimulating depending on water temperature and infant preference. Slightly warm water with minimal splashing tends to be more conducive to sleep preparation than vigorous bath play.\n\n## Timing and Consistency\n\nBedtime routines should begin at the same time each evening, supporting the development of circadian rhythm consolidation. Consistency across days, even weekends, maximizes the neurobiological benefit. Most infants and toddlers thrive with bedtime between 7 and 8 p.m., though individual variation exists based on family schedule and natural circadian preferences.\n\nThe routine should transition gradually from day activities rather than suddenly shifting to evening. Activities like dimming household lights 1-2 hours before bedtime, reducing noise levels, and decreasing stimulating play in the hour before the formal routine begins support circadian adjustment.\n\n## Reading and Language Development\n\nIncluding picture books or stories in the bedtime routine provides benefits beyond sleep facilitation. Early and frequent reading exposure supports language development, preliteracy skills, and the development of positive associations with books. Short picture books work well for infants and young toddlers, while older toddlers enjoy longer stories.\n\nReading together creates opportunities for physical closeness and emotional connection that strengthen parent-infant relationships. The repetitive nature of reading the same stories night after night, while potentially boring for adults, provides comfort and predictability that infants find soothing.\n\n## Physical Environment Preparation\n\nAs the routine nears completion, environmental adjustments signal the body that sleep is imminent. Turning off overhead lights in favor of dim, warm lighting activates melatonin production. Temperature in the sleep room should be cool, approximately 68-72 degrees Fahrenheit, supporting the thermoregulation needed for quality sleep.\n\nAll screen use should cease at least 1-2 hours before bedtime, as blue light from screens suppresses melatonin and increases alertness. Instead, hands-on activities like reading, music, or quiet play with tactile toys maintain engagement without neurobiological sleep disruption.\n\n## Troubleshooting Common Issues\n\nIf bedtime routines produce escalating requests for additional stories or delays, establish clear boundaries before starting. Announcing that ''this is the last story'' or using visual timers helps children understand what to expect. Firmly but kindly redirecting requests back to sleep without hostility maintains the emotionally positive tone needed for success.\n\nIf routines extend beyond 45 minutes despite focused efforts, simplifying the routine by eliminating one activity and extending the pre-routine wind-down period often helps. Some families find success with brief ''check-in'' visits after leaving the room rather than extended routines that delay separation and sleep onset.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  12,
  156,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Navigating Sleep Regressions',
  'navigating-sleep-regressions',
  'Understand common sleep regressions, their developmental basis, and strategies for managing them.',
  E'# Navigating Sleep Regressions\n\nSleep regressions—temporary periods of disrupted sleep despite previously established good sleep habits—are normal developmental phenomena that occur as infants'' brains undergo significant maturation. Understanding the developmental basis and expected duration of regressions helps parents respond calmly rather than abandoning effective sleep strategies during temporary setbacks.\n\n## Common Regression Periods\n\nThe 4-month sleep regression coincides with major changes in sleep architecture as REM sleep organization matures. Infants'' sleep cycles consolidate and deepen, temporarily disrupting the light, easily maintained sleep of younger infants. This regression affects most infants, typically lasting 2-6 weeks.\n\nThe 8-month regression often coincides with separation anxiety development and increased mobility. Infants become more aware of caregiver absence and more mobile in the crib, both factors disrupting sleep. The 12-month regression frequently accompanies language development, cognitive leaps, and the neurological changes supporting increased motor skills.\n\nOther sleep regressions occur around 18 months and 2-3 years, coinciding with language explosions, toilet training readiness, and increased autonomy and independence. While exact timing varies individually, awareness of these developmental windows helps parents recognize regressions as temporary rather than permanent setbacks.\n\n## Recognizing Regression vs. Illness or Hunger\n\nActual regressions appear suddenly in infants previously sleeping well without obvious cause. The infant returns to patterns from earlier developmental stages—frequent waking, difficulty falling asleep, or extended nighttime wake periods—without fever, pain, or other signs of acute illness.\n\nBefore assuming a regression, rule out other causes of sleep disruption. Teething pain, ear infections, gastroesophageal reflux, hunger (particularly during growth spurts), developmental discomfort from new mobility, or environmental changes might explain sleep changes and warrant specific interventions beyond standard regression management.\n\n## Response Strategies\n\nDuring regressions, parents should maintain established sleep routines and consistent responses while showing extra patience and empathy. The infant is not behaving badly intentionally but rather struggling with developmental changes affecting sleep capacity. Temporary increases in nighttime parental involvement—such as additional soothing or brief bed-sharing—can ease the transition without permanently disrupting sleep habits.\n\nConsistently implementing the same responses used during better-sleep periods signals to the infant that sleep expectations remain unchanged. If sleep training methods were previously used, maintaining consistency proves important, as regressive behavior typically resolves more quickly when expectations stay constant.\n\n## Duration and Resolution\n\nMost regressions resolve within 1-6 weeks as the infant's nervous system adjusts to new developmental capabilities. Sleep typically improves as rapidly as it deteriorated without requiring intervention changes. Some regression periods extend longer if concurrent developmental challenges occur simultaneously.\n\nKeeping sleep logs during regressions helps parents track patterns and recognize when the disruption is resolving. This objective documentation prevents the tendency to catastrophize temporary setbacks. Communicating with your pediatrician about regression timing and characteristics provides reassurance and guidance specific to your infant\'s individual development.',
  'article',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  16,
  104,
  'published',
  false
);

-- SAFETY RESOURCES
INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Childproofing Your Home Room by Room',
  'childproofing-home-room-room',
  'Complete checklist for identifying and eliminating hazards throughout your home.',
  E'# Childproofing Your Home Room by Room\n\n## Kitchen Hazards and Safety Measures\n\nThe kitchen presents multiple hazards requiring systematic attention. Store all medications, cleaning supplies, and dangerous substances in locked cabinets or high shelves beyond reach. Ensure cabinet locks are sturdy and resist repeated testing by curious toddlers.\n\nKnobs and handles on ovens, stovetops, and drawers containing sharp objects need protective devices. Use back burners when cooking and keep pot handles turned inward to prevent reaching. Keep electrical cords from appliances wrapped or secured to prevent pulling. Secure the refrigerator if your child can access it to prevent weight-related tipping hazards.\n\n## Living Areas and General Spaces\n\nRemove or secure furniture that could tip when climbed or pulled, including bookshelves, dressers, and entertainment units. Use furniture anchors to secure pieces to walls. Remove decorative items from low tables that could be pulled down. Ensure all electrical outlets are covered with tamper-resistant outlet covers or dummy plugs.\n\nSecure window blind cords and drape cords out of reach to prevent strangulation hazards. Install window guards on windows above the first floor. Cover hard furniture corners with edge guards or corner protectors. Keep houseplants, including toxic varieties like philodendron and dieffenbachia, out of reach or eliminate them entirely.\n\n## Bathrooms\n\nNever leave standing water in tubs or buckets, as infants and toddlers can drown in 1-2 inches of water. Set water heater temperature to 120 degrees Fahrenheit to prevent scalding. Install tub temperature monitors to alert caregivers to dangerous water temperatures.\n\nStore all medications, supplements, and toiletries in locked cabinets. Drain and store toilet seats in locked position or install automatic toilet-seat locks. Ensure bath toys are free of mold and stored in mesh bags allowing drainage. Remove extension cords and electrical appliances from bathroom access areas.\n\n## Bedrooms and Sleep Areas\n\nKeep cribs away from windows with corded blinds. Do not hang wall decorations above sleep surfaces. Ensure bumper pads are firmly secured if used. Once infants show climbing ability, remove decorative items from dresser tops and ensure dressers are anchored.\n\nSecure pillows, blankets, and soft objects in a separate location rather than the sleep space. Inspect mattresses regularly for wear or exposed springs. Keep nightlights dimly lit and positioned away from the infant's direct line of sight to prevent visual stimulation.\n\n## Stairways and Falls\n\nInstall safety gates at the top and bottom of all stairways. Ensure gates are properly installed and cannot be pushed open by a determined toddler. Keep stairs clear of toys and other tripping hazards. Install handrails at appropriate height for toddlers to use when learning to navigate stairs independently.\n\nRemove throw rugs from stairs and slippery flooring. Ensure stair treads have adequate traction. Close off access to balconies and decks with secure barriers. Test all gates, railings, and protective barriers regularly to ensure they remain secure.\n\n## Specific Equipment and Hazard Prevention\n\nChoking hazards include small objects, coins, small toys, and foods. Perform a thorough floor search on hands and knees, viewing the space from a toddler''s perspective. Remove balloons, plastic bags, and small parts from toys. Cut grapes and hot dogs lengthwise and then in quarters to prevent choking.\n\nRegularly inspect toys for age-appropriateness and signs of wear. Keep cords, strings, and ribbons inaccessible. Store heavy objects securely to prevent tipping. Install carbon monoxide detectors and smoke detectors, testing regularly and replacing batteries twice yearly.',
  'checklist',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  20,
  156,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Car Seat Safety: Choosing and Installing Correctly',
  'car-seat-safety-choosing-installing',
  'Essential guidance on selecting appropriate car seats and ensuring correct installation.',
  E'# Car Seat Safety: Choosing and Installing Correctly\n\n## Car Seat Types and Selection\n\nCar seats fall into several categories based on a child''s age, weight, and height. Infants from birth (typically 5-9 pounds) through approximately 12 months should use rear-facing infant car seats or convertible seats in rear-facing mode. Infants'' developing necks and spines require the support that rear-facing seating provides.\n\nConvertible car seats accommodate children from birth through age 3-4 (typically 5-65 pounds) by transitioning from rear-facing to forward-facing mode. These seats prove economical but occupy more space than dedicated infant seats. Booster seats serve older children (typically age 4-8, weighing 40-100 pounds) by elevating them to ensure proper seat belt fit.\n\nAll-in-one seats attempt to serve all stages but often do not perform optimally at any single stage. When selecting any car seat, verify it meets current federal safety standards (FMVSS 213). Check expiration dates and recall status before purchase or use of any seat, as old seats may have structural degradation and recalled seats pose known hazards.\n\n## Proper Installation\n\nCorrect installation is critical for maximum protection. The seat should not move more than one inch side-to-side or front-to-back when tested at the belt path with firm pressure. Most installations are performed incorrectly, reducing protective capability significantly. Consulting a certified car seat technician provides invaluable assurance.\n\nInstallation methods vary between vehicles and car seats. Lower anchors (LATCH system) provide an alternative to seat belts for children weighing under 65 pounds. Some vehicles have stronger lower anchors than others; consult your vehicle manual and car seat instructions regarding appropriate installation method for your specific vehicle and car seat combination.\n\nFor rear-facing seats, recline angle is important to prevent slumping and airway obstruction. Most infant car seats have adjusters; follow specific instructions for your seat model. Rear-facing angle should be approximately 45 degrees, not flat. Check angle using the level indicator on most infant seats.\n\n## Harness and Fit\n\nHarnesses should be snug, with no more than one finger of space between the harness and your child''s shoulder. The harness should enter the seat at or slightly below shoulder height for rear-facing seats. Check harness tightness regularly, as infants wearing bulky clothing may be strapped too loosely when clothing is removed.\n\nRemove bulky coats and winter clothing before fastening harnesses, as these items compress under pressure and create gaps between harness and child. Instead, fasten the harness first, then drape a coat over the top for warmth. This maintains proper restraint while protecting from cold.\n\n## Transitioning Between Seats\n\nKeep children rear-facing as long as possible—ideally until age 2 or when they exceed the rear-facing weight/height limits of the seat. Children are five times safer in rear-facing seats. Many families transition too early to forward-facing seats, sacrificing significant protection.\n\nWhen transitioning to booster seats, use seats with backs initially, as they provide more protection in side-impact crashes than backless boosters. Position booster seats in the middle of the back seat when possible, as this location offers additional protection. Do not move to seat belts alone until children are approximately 4''10\" tall and can sit properly for entire trips (feet flat, back against seat, knees bent).\n\n## Additional Safety Practices\n\nNever leave children unattended in cars, even briefly, as temperatures can reach dangerous levels rapidly. Never use car seats outside the vehicle for extended periods—infants should not spend long durations in car seats, as this position can compromise airway in some infants.\n\nRegularly inspect car seats for signs of damage from accidents. Even minor accidents may compromise structural integrity invisibly. Most manufacturers recommend replacement after any accident. Visit certified technician clinics for free installation checks to ensure correct setup maintains protection throughout your child''s use.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.nhtsa.gov/child-safety/car-seats-and-booster-seats',
  -4,
  260,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Water Safety and Drowning Prevention',
  'water-safety-drowning-prevention',
  'Comprehensive overview of water safety strategies for infants and young children.',
  E'# Water Safety and Drowning Prevention\n\n## Drowning Risk and Supervision\n\nDrowning is a leading cause of unintentional death in children ages 1-4, yet is entirely preventable through appropriate supervision and environmental controls. Drowning can occur silently and rapidly, in seconds, with the child unable to call for help. Young children lack the cognitive or physical capability to self-rescue in water, making constant supervision non-negotiable.\n\nDesignate one adult as the primary water watcher during any water exposure, whether at pools, beaches, or home bathtubs. This person should remain focused on the child, free from distractions like phones or conversation. In settings with lifeguards, parental supervision remains critical, as lifeguards cannot monitor individual children the way parents can.\n\n## Bathing and Household Water\n\nInfants and toddlers can drown in as little as 1-2 inches of water in seconds. Never leave infants or toddlers unattended in or near bathtubs, even momentarily, even to answer phones or doors. If you must leave the bathroom, remove your child from the water and take them with you.\n\nUse bath seats that tether to the tub to prevent infants from sliding beneath water, understanding that these devices do not replace supervision. Keep all bathtub drain valves secured with drain guards. Drain pools and hot tubs completely when not in use, or ensure they are fenced with self-closing, self-latching gates preventing unauthorized access.\n\n## Pool and Beach Safety\n\nFences completely surrounding pools, including pools at residential homes, should be at least 4 feet high with self-closing, self-latching gates. The fence should prevent gap access that would allow small children to slip through. Remove access points like adjacent deck furniture that allows children to climb over fences.\n\nInstall safety covers and alarms on pools when not in use as supplementary protective measures. Maintain clear visibility of the pool area from inside your home. Teach children water safety rules verbally, but understand that very young children cannot reliably follow rules—environment and supervision remain the primary protective factors.\n\n## Recognizing Drowning\n\nDrowning often appears different from portrayals in media. A child drowning may not call out or wave arms dramatically. Instead, watch for bobbing beneath water, vertical positioning in the water with minimal limb movement, or glassy-eyed expressions. Gasping or coughing water could indicate imminent drowning or recent near-drowning requiring immediate attention.\n\nAfter water exposure, watch for delayed drowning symptoms (secondary drowning) including coughing, lethargy, difficulty breathing, or vomiting. While rare, secondary drowning can occur hours after water exposure. Any concerning symptoms warrant immediate medical evaluation.\n\n## Protective Equipment and Skills\n\nLife jackets, properly fitted and fastened, provide an additional layer of protection for children in or near water. However, life jackets are supplementary to supervision—never assume a life jacket makes a child safe without constant attention. Swimming lessons provide some protective value in older children but are not recommended before age 1 and do not prevent drowning in very young children.\n\nParents and caregivers should maintain current CPR and first aid certification, as early CPR significantly improves outcomes for children who experience near-drowning incidents. Keep rescue equipment and phones accessible near pools. Teach children basic water rules like staying away from drain areas and not running near pools, while recognizing these rules cannot be reliably followed by young children.',
  'article',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  0,
  260,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Poison Prevention in the Home',
  'poison-prevention-home',
  'Identify common poisons and implement safety measures to prevent accidental poisoning.',
  E'# Poison Prevention in the Home\n\n## Common Household Poisons\n\nMedications represent the most common source of poisoning in young children, particularly over-the-counter pain relievers, cold medications, and prescription medications accessible to curious toddlers. Store all medications, including vitamins and supplements, in locked cabinets or secured in original containers with child-resistant caps.\n\nCleaning products, including disinfectants, bleach, drain cleaners, and laundry detergents, contain toxic chemicals. Single-use detergent pods present particular risk, as their bright colors attract young children who may ingest or bite them, releasing high concentrations of chemicals. Store all cleaning products in locked cabinets below sinks and never transfer products to unmarked containers.\n\nPersonal care products like cosmetics, deodorants, toothpaste, and mouthwash contain potentially toxic substances. Nail products, perfumes, and alcohols should be stored in locked areas. Alcoholic beverages, while intended for adults, are frequently accessible to toddlers and present overdose risks.\n\n## Substances from Outdoor and Garden Areas\n\nPesticides, herbicides, and fertilizers applied to lawns and gardens can poison children through ingestion or skin exposure. Keep children away from treated areas for the recommended time period specified on product labels. Store all pesticides in locked cabinets or sheds in original labeled containers.\n\nPlants present varied poisoning risks—some cause mild irritation while others cause severe systemic effects. Toxic houseplants include dieffenbachia, philodendron, oleander, foxglove, and yew. Identify plants in your home and yard and remove toxic varieties. Keep ornamental bulbs, particularly daffodils and amaryllis, stored safely away from children.\n\nCarbon monoxide, though invisible, represents a serious poisoning hazard from appliances, generators, and vehicle exhaust. Install carbon monoxide detectors in your home and have heating appliances inspected annually. Never run generators, grills, or other fuel-burning equipment inside homes or attached garages.\n\n## Storage and Prevention Strategies\n\nCreate a comprehensive inventory of potentially toxic substances in your home, including all medications, supplements, cleaning products, personal care items, pesticides, and automotive supplies. Organize these items in locked cabinets in locations where children cannot gain access even with climbing or persistence.\n\nUse child-resistant closures on medication bottles, though recognize these are not childproof—they only slow access. Discard medications safely according to FDA guidelines rather than flushing or throwing them in trash where children or pets could access them. Never tell children that medication is ''candy'' or ''vitamins'' to encourage consumption—always use accurate language about substance purposes.\n\n## Responding to Poisoning\n\nIn case of suspected poisoning, immediately call the Poison Control Center at 1-800-222-1222 (available 24/7) rather than 911 unless the child is unconscious or having seizures. Have the product container, chemical name, and amount ingested readily available when you call. Do not induce vomiting, as this can cause additional damage depending on the substance ingested.\n\nPoisin Control specialists provide specific guidance based on the substance involved, the child''s age and weight, and the amount ingested. Follow their recommendations precisely. Even if your child appears asymptomatic, complete the Poison Control assessment, as some substances have delayed effects.\n\n## Teaching Children About Poison Prevention\n\nTeach older toddlers and preschoolers that medications and cleaning supplies are not for children and should only be handled by trusted adults. Use simple language: "This will make us sick." Reinforce that eating plants, mushrooms, or items from yards and gardens requires adult permission. While young children cannot reliably follow these rules, repetition builds understanding over time.',
  'checklist',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  20,
  260,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Safe Sleep Environment Checklist',
  'safe-sleep-environment-checklist',
  'Complete checklist for ensuring your infant''s sleep space meets safety standards.',
  E'# Safe Sleep Environment Checklist\n\n## Sleep Surface Requirements\n\nInfant sleep surface must be firm and flat. Acceptable surfaces include full-size cribs, mini cribs, portable playpens that meet safety standards, bassinets designed for sleep, and play yards. The mattress should fit snugly with no gaps between mattress and crib sides where an infant could wedge.\n\nInspect the sleep surface before use for broken slats, splintered wood, or structural damage. Ensure crib drop-sides (if applicable) are secure and cannot be released accidentally. Verify all hardware is tight and secure. Portable cribs and playpens should have taut, intact fabric and sturdy frame construction.\n\nMattresses should have fitted sheets designed specifically for your crib dimensions. Ensure fitted sheets are truly fitted, not flat sheets tucked under the mattress, which can slip and create suffocation hazards. Use only one fitted sheet directly on the mattress with no additional padding, mattress covers, or waterproof layers underneath.\n\n## Sleep Space Organization\n\nThe sleep space must be completely bare. Remove all pillows, blankets, bumper pads, sleep positioners, and soft objects from the crib or bassinet. Blankets, including quilts and comforters, should never be in the sleep space. If using a sleep sack or wearable blanket, ensure it fits snugly and correctly to prevent the infant from slipping underneath.\n\nRemove from the sleep space any hanging decorations, crib toys attached above the sleeping area, or dangling objects that could fall on the infant. Wall decorations above the crib should be removed as well. Keep cords, strings, or ribbons away from the sleep area.\n\nIf using a pacifier, attach it with a short ribbon only long enough to reach the infant''s mouth, not the full length across the crib. Discard pacifiers with broken attachments. Some families choose to skip pacifiers until sleep is established to avoid this complication.\n\n## Environmental Controls\n\nMaintain room temperature in a comfortable range, typically 68-72 degrees Fahrenheit. Overdressing, excessive blankets, or overheating is associated with increased SIDS risk. Dress the infant appropriately for room temperature using a sleep sack rather than blankets.\n\nKeep the sleep room quiet but consider that complete silence is not necessary. Many infants sleep well with white noise or consistent background sounds that mask environmental changes. Ensure any sound machines use age-appropriate volume levels.\n\nLighting should be minimal during night sleep periods. A dim nightlight is acceptable if needed for parent visibility during nighttime care. However, bright light exposure at night can disrupt sleep and melatonin production. During daytime sleep or naps, normal room lighting is appropriate.\n\n## Room-Sharing Without Bed-Sharing\n\nKeep the infant''s sleep space in your room, visible and accessible but separate, for at least the first 6 months and ideally the first year. This proximity enables responsive nighttime care while eliminating bed-sharing risks. If space is limited, placing the bassinet or portable crib immediately adjacent to the adult bed maintains the protective benefit of room-sharing.\n\nEnsure your bed is not adjacent to the infant''s sleep surface in a way that would allow the infant to roll onto your bed or into gaps. Keep any furniture or objects away from the infant''s sleep space that could create entrapment hazards.\n\n## Weekly Maintenance and Inspection\n\nWeekly, inspect the sleep surface for debris, broken parts, or hazards. Wash sleep surfaces and bedding according to manufacturer instructions. Check that all anchoring systems, if used, remain secure. Verify that any attached devices like monitors are securely fastened.\n\nCheck room temperature regularly, especially during seasonal changes. Ensure window coverings are secured and present no strangulation risks. Verify that any recalled products are no longer in use. Keep the phone nearby for emergency access if needed during nighttime sleep periods.',
  'checklist',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care-and-public-health/aap-healthy-children-magazine/',
  0,
  52,
  'published',
  false
);
