INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Understanding the Recommended Childhood Vaccine Schedule',
  'vaccine-schedule-overview',
  'Learn about the CDC-recommended immunization schedule that protects children from 14 preventable diseases from birth through age 18.',
  E'# Understanding the Recommended Childhood Vaccine Schedule\n\nThe childhood immunization schedule is a carefully developed roadmap created by the CDC, American Academy of Pediatrics, and other health organizations to provide maximum protection during the vulnerable early years of life.\n\n## Why the Schedule Matters\n\nThe timing of vaccines is based on two critical factors: the age when children are most vulnerable to specific diseases and when their immune systems are most likely to respond effectively to vaccination. Newborns receive some immunity from their mothers, but this protection wanes over the first months of life, creating windows of vulnerability. The recommended schedule addresses these gaps with optimal precision.\n\n## Birth Through Age 2 Vaccines\n\nInfants receive protection against hepatitis B within hours of birth, followed by rotavirus, diphtheria, tetanus, pertussis, polio, and pneumococcal disease during the first year. Each vaccine addresses diseases that historically caused significant infant mortality. Hepatitis B, for instance, can lead to chronic infection and liver disease; pertussis remains a serious threat to infants who cannot be fully protected until they complete their initial series.\n\n## Toddler and Preschool Years\n\nBetween ages 1 and 5, children receive booster doses to maintain immunity and complete series against additional diseases like measles, mumps, varicella, and hepatitis A. During this period, children also receive protection against seasonal influenza through annual vaccination.\n\n## School-Age and Adolescent Updates\n\nAdditional doses at ages 4-6 and 11-12 years ensure sustained immunity. Adolescents receive meningococcal protection starting at age 11, human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccine beginning at age 11, and tetanus/diphtheria/pertussis boosters during the teen years.\n\n## Tracking Your Child''s Progress\n\nParents should maintain accurate records of their child''s vaccinations and bring documentation to each appointment. These records are essential for school enrollment and may be needed for travel. Many pediatric practices now offer digital vaccination records that parents can access through patient portals.\n\n## Catching Up on Missed Doses\n\nIf your child has fallen behind on vaccinations, speak with your healthcare provider about a catch-up schedule. No vaccine needs to be restarted regardless of the interval since the previous dose; your provider can resume from where your child left off.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/schedules/hcp/imz/child-adolescent.html',
  0,
  260,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'What to Expect at Your Baby''s Vaccination Appointments',
  'vaccination-appointment-guide',
  'Practical guidance for preparing for and understanding what happens during routine immunization visits with your pediatrician.',
  E'# What to Expect at Your Baby''s Vaccination Appointments\n\nVaccination appointments are a cornerstone of infant and childhood health maintenance. Understanding the process helps parents prepare emotionally and practically for these visits.\n\n## Before the Appointment\n\nArrive early to complete any necessary paperwork and update your contact information. Bring your child''s vaccination record or previous appointment documentation. Consider scheduling appointments when your child is typically well-rested and calm—often in the morning or early afternoon works best. Some parents find it helpful to plan a calming activity afterward, like a quiet time at home or a gentle car ride.\n\nIf your baby has been recently ill or you''re concerned about timing, discuss this with your provider before the visit. Generally, minor illnesses without fever are not a reason to delay vaccination, but your pediatrician can assess your specific situation.\n\n## During the Appointment\n\nYour provider will review your child''s health history and current status before administration. They may ask about any reactions to previous vaccines or family history of adverse reactions. Be honest about your concerns—your pediatrician is there to address them and ensure your child''s safety.\n\nThe provider will typically administer multiple vaccines simultaneously, using different injection sites. While it may feel overwhelming to see multiple injections, this approach keeps your child''s appointments on schedule and reduces overall stress from frequent visits.\n\n## What Your Baby May Experience\n\nInfants typically cry immediately after injection—this is a normal pain response and generally resolves within seconds to minutes. Offer comfort through holding, soothing voices, and physical closeness. Feeding (breast or bottle) during vaccination can provide comfort and distraction.\n\nSome vaccines are given orally (rotavirus), which many parents find less distressing than injections. Your pediatrician will explain which vaccines will be administered and how.\n\n## After the Appointment\n\nYour provider will give you a vaccine information sheet for each vaccine administered. Review this carefully, as it contains important information about side effects and what to monitor. You''ll receive an updated vaccination record to keep in your files.\n\n## Common Questions to Ask\n\nAsk your provider about expected reactions, what symptoms warrant a call, and when to return for the next appointment. Clarify any gaps in the schedule and discuss any special circumstances affecting your child''s vaccination plan. Don''t hesitate to ask for written materials or reliable online resources for additional information.',
  'article',
  'https://www.aap.org/en/patient-care/immunizations/',
  0,
  78,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Common Vaccine Side Effects and How to Manage Them',
  'vaccine-side-effects-management',
  'An evidence-based overview of expected and rare vaccine reactions, plus strategies to minimize discomfort and know when to seek medical attention.',
  E'# Common Vaccine Side Effects and How to Manage Them\n\nVaccines are among the safest medical interventions available, yet understanding potential side effects helps parents know what to expect and how to respond appropriately.\n\n## Expected, Mild Reactions\n\nMost vaccine reactions are mild and temporary, occurring in the hours or days after vaccination. Soreness, redness, or swelling at the injection site affects 10-40% of children, depending on the vaccine. This local reaction typically peaks 24-48 hours after vaccination and resolves within several days.\n\nFever within 24-48 hours after vaccination is common, particularly after vaccines like pneumococcal and diphtheria/tetanus/pertussis (DTaP). This fever response indicates the immune system is active and mounting protection. In most cases, fever remains below 102°F and requires only comfort measures.\n\nLow-grade fever and mild fussiness represent your child''s immune system responding appropriately to the vaccine. These reactions do not indicate that the vaccine is harmful; rather, they demonstrate immunological engagement.\n\n## Managing Common Reactions\n\nFor injection site soreness, applying a cool compress in the first 24 hours can provide relief, followed by warm compresses if soreness persists. Movement and gentle massage also help reduce localized discomfort.\n\nFor fever and fussiness, acetaminophen or ibuprofen (in children old enough for these medications) can be administered according to age-appropriate dosing. Ensure adequate hydration, particularly if fever is present. Offer frequent feeds or drinks. Dress your child appropriately for comfort—avoid over-bundling, which can trap heat.\n\nKeep your child home from school or childcare if fever is present, both for comfort and to prevent spread of any concurrent illness. Most fevers resolve within 24-48 hours.\n\n## Serious but Rare Reactions\n\nAllegic reactions to vaccine components occur rarely, typically within minutes to hours of vaccination. Symptoms include difficulty breathing, hives, swelling of lips or tongue, or severe dizziness. Medical providers administering vaccines are equipped to manage allergic reactions immediately.\n\nGillain-Barré syndrome, a rare neurological condition, has been associated with certain vaccines in extremely small numbers of cases. The risk of this condition from vaccination is far lower than the risk from the actual diseases themselves.\n\n## When to Contact Your Provider\n\nContact your pediatrician if you observe unusual behavior, persistent crying lasting more than 3 hours, temperature above 103°F without responsive fever reduction, or any concerning symptoms developing in the days after vaccination.\n\nSevere allergic reactions require emergency care. However, the overwhelming majority of children recover completely from vaccines without serious complications, while protection against dangerous diseases is gained.',
  'article',
  'https://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/hcp/conversations/downloads/vacsafe-adversevents-office.pdf',
  0,
  260,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Herd Immunity and Why Vaccination Rates Matter',
  'herd-immunity-community-protection',
  'Understand how community vaccination rates protect vulnerable individuals who cannot be vaccinated and why population-level immunization is crucial for disease control.',
  E'# Herd Immunity and Why Vaccination Rates Matter\n\nVaccination creates protection at two levels: individual and community. Herd immunity—also called community immunity—is a critical public health concept that explains why vaccination rates matter even for healthy, well-protected individuals.\n\n## How Herd Immunity Works\n\nWhen a sufficient percentage of a population is vaccinated against a contagious disease, transmission becomes difficult. The virus or bacterium cannot find enough susceptible hosts to establish chains of transmission. This creates a protective barrier around vulnerable individuals—newborns too young for certain vaccines, people with immunosuppression, those with severe allergies to vaccine components, and the small percentage of vaccinated individuals whose immune systems don''t develop adequate protection.\n\nThe threshold varies by disease. Measles requires approximately 95% population immunity to maintain herd immunity. Polio requires roughly 85-95%. Whooping cough requires approximately 85%. When communities fall below these thresholds, outbreaks occur, often affecting the most vulnerable first.\n\n## Why Vulnerable Populations Depend on Herd Immunity\n\nNewborns cannot receive many vaccines until specific ages when their immune systems are mature enough to respond effectively. During the first weeks and months, protection relies heavily on herd immunity and maternal antibodies. Infants hospitalized in neonatal intensive care units are particularly vulnerable and depend entirely on community protection.\n\nImmunnocompromised individuals—children undergoing cancer treatment, those with primary immunodeficiency disorders, organ transplant recipients—cannot be vaccinated or may not develop adequate immunity even with vaccination. These individuals' survival depends on robust community vaccination rates.\n\nPregnant individuals cannot receive live attenuated vaccines and may have other vaccination limitations. Their fetuses, particularly in the first and early second trimester when many organs are developing, depend on community-level disease control.\n\n## The Obligation to Community\n\nWhen vaccination rates decline in communities, protection erodes systematically. Historical data demonstrates this principle: following reductions in measles vaccination rates in specific communities, measles outbreaks occurred, sometimes resulting in deaths among unvaccinated and vulnerable individuals.\n\nMaintaining herd immunity represents a collective responsibility. Each vaccination decision affects not only the individual child but also the surrounding community. This is particularly important when families have choice about vaccination—those with medical access and ability to vaccinate have a special responsibility to ensure community protection for those without equivalent access.\n\n## Vaccination and Disease Elimination\n\nSeveral diseases have been eliminated or nearly eliminated globally through sustained high vaccination rates. Smallpox is eradicated. Polio exists in only a handful of countries. These achievements demonstrate the power of sustained, community-wide vaccination commitment.\n\nMaintaining vaccination rates sufficient for herd immunity is essential to prevent the return of diseases that once killed thousands of children annually.',
  'article',
  'https://www.who.int/news-room/questions-and-answers/item/vaccines-and-immunization-herd-immunity',
  0,
  260,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Vaccines During Pregnancy: Tdap, Flu, and COVID-19',
  'maternal-vaccination-safety',
  'Evidence-based guidance on vaccine safety during pregnancy and how maternal vaccination protects both mother and developing baby.',
  E'# Vaccines During Pregnancy: Tdap, Flu, and COVID-19\n\nVaccination during pregnancy is one of the most evidence-supported interventions for protecting both pregnant individuals and their fetuses. Multiple professional organizations, including ACOG, CDC, and WHO, recommend specific vaccines during pregnancy.\n\n## The Safety Profile of Pregnancy Vaccination\n\nInactivated vaccines (vaccines made from killed virus or bacterial components) are safe during all stages of pregnancy. These vaccines cannot cause infection in the pregnant individual or developing fetus. Live attenuated vaccines should generally be avoided during pregnancy, but inactivated vaccines pose no risk.\n\nThe decision to vaccinate during pregnancy involves weighing the vaccine''s safety profile—which is excellent for inactivated vaccines—against the risk of the disease to the pregnant individual and fetus. In every case where an inactivated vaccine has been evaluated for pregnancy use, the benefits of disease prevention far exceed any theoretical risks.\n\n## Tetanus, Diphtheria, and Acellular Pertussis (Tdap)\n\nTdap vaccination during pregnancy, ideally in the third trimester (weeks 27-36), provides maximum maternal protection and transfers pertussis-specific antibodies to the fetus. These maternal antibodies provide crucial protection in the first weeks after birth, when pertussis poses significant risk.\n\nPertussis in newborns can be severe, causing severe coughing fits that disrupt feeding and breathing, and potentially leading to pneumonia or seizures. Maternal immunization dramatically reduces risk of pertussis in infants under 3 months of age.\n\nPregnant individuals should receive Tdap during each pregnancy, even if previously vaccinated. This ensures maximum antibody transfer and fresh immunity for the newborn period.\n\n## Influenza Vaccination During Pregnancy\n\nAnnual flu vaccination is recommended for all pregnant individuals, regardless of trimester. Pregnant individuals are at higher risk for severe influenza complications, including pneumonia and hospitalization. Additionally, maternal vaccination provides protection to the developing fetus and newborn.\n\nMaternal influenza antibodies protect infants through the first months of life, when they are too young for their own flu vaccination. Studies consistently demonstrate that infants born to vaccinated mothers have lower rates of influenza infection and severe disease in early infancy.\n\n## COVID-19 Vaccination in Pregnancy\n\nCOVID-19 vaccination during pregnancy is recommended by CDC, ACOG, and major global health organizations. Pregnant individuals are at higher risk for severe COVID-19, particularly in the second and third trimesters. Additionally, pregnant individuals who are vaccinated or previously infected transfer protective antibodies to their fetuses and newborns.\n\nExtensive safety monitoring of millions of pregnant individuals who received COVID-19 vaccines has demonstrated no increase in miscarriage, stillbirth, or birth defects. Infants born to vaccinated mothers show lower rates of COVID-19 infection and hospitalization in early life.\n\n## Benefits to the Newborn\n\nMaternal immunization creates a period of passive immunity in newborns. Antibodies transferred across the placenta and through breast milk provide protection until the infant''s own immune system matures and vaccination series are completed. This represents a critical protective window for diseases like pertussis and influenza that pose significant risk to very young infants.\n\n## Discussion with Healthcare Providers\n\nPregnant individuals should discuss vaccination plans with their obstetrician or midwife. Individual circumstances, including pregnancy trimester, medical history, and disease prevalence in the community, guide recommendations. In all cases, the evidence demonstrates that recommended vaccines are safe and protect both mother and baby.',
  'article',
  'https://www.acog.org/clinical-information/immunization-vaccination-and-other-clinical-guidance/vaccines-during-pregnancy',
  -40,
  0,
  'published',
  false
);

