INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Building a Strong Parent-Child Bond from Day One',
  'parent-child-bonding-newborn',
  'Evidence-based strategies for establishing secure attachment and fostering the parent-child relationship during infancy''s critical early months.',
  E'# Building a Strong Parent-Child Bond from Day One\n\nThe bond between parent and child forms the foundation for emotional security, social development, and resilience throughout life. Neuroscience research demonstrates that early attachment relationships literally shape brain development, with implications for learning, relationships, and emotional regulation across the lifespan.\n\n## What Bonding Actually Means\n\nParent-child bonding is not a single magical moment occurring at birth. Rather, it develops through thousands of small, responsive interactions—a process called "serve and return" communication. When a baby cries and a parent responds, when a baby gurgles and a parent smiles back, neural connections strengthen. Consistency and responsiveness build trust.\n\nSecure attachment develops when infants learn they can depend on their parent or caregiver. This doesn''t mean responding to every cry instantly—infants need some experience with minor frustration to develop self-regulation skills. Rather, it means responding warmly and consistently most of the time, creating predictability and safety.\n\n## Early Weeks Connection\n\nSkin-to-skin contact in the first hours and days after birth supports both physical and emotional bonding. This contact regulates infant temperature, heart rate, and breathing while facilitating oxytocin release in both parent and baby—the "bonding hormone" that strengthens attachment.\n\nDuring the newborn period, spend unhurried time observing your baby. Notice their preferences: Do they prefer certain sounds? Which pacifier style do they favor? What positions seem most calming? This observation deepens your understanding of your unique infant and builds confidence in your parenting.\n\n## Responsive Feeding\n\nWhether breast or bottle feeding, feed-time represents prime bonding opportunity. Hold your baby close. Make eye contact. Respond to your baby''s feeding cues—watching for signs of hunger and satiety rather than forcing a schedule. This responsive feeding teaches your baby that their signals matter and that their needs will be met.\n\nBoth breastfeeding and bottle feeding can facilitate bonding when they occur in a calm, responsive context. The critical element is the emotional presence and attentiveness of the caregiver, not the feeding method.\n\n## Responsiveness to Communication\n\nNewborns communicate primarily through crying, but they also communicate through gaze, sounds, and movements. When you respond to these signals—changing a diaper, addressing hunger, responding to the baby''s gaze by smiling back—you''re building a conversation. Your baby learns that they can affect their world and that you understand them.\n\nNot every cry requires the same response. Sometimes your baby needs feeding; sometimes they need to be held; sometimes they need space to settle. Over weeks and months, you''ll increasingly recognize what different cries and signals mean, deepening your responsiveness.\n\n## Managing Bonding Anxiety\n\nNot all parents experience immediate bonding feelings. Some parents feel disconnection or even resentment early on, particularly if they''re exhausted, struggling with postpartum mood disorders, or had complicated births. These experiences are common and do not indicate parental inadequacy.\n\nBonding develops through action and time, not just emotion. Engaging in responsive caregiving—even when emotional connection feels absent—builds the foundation for later attachment security. Seek support from healthcare providers or therapists if you''re concerned about bonding, particularly if mood or anxiety symptoms are present.\n\n## Special Circumstances\n\nAdopted infants, babies separated from birth parents, and infants with medical complications can develop secure attachments. Consistent, responsive care facilitates bonding regardless of how the family formed or what early challenges occurred. If bonding feels particularly difficult, professional support from attachment specialists is available.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.zerotothree.org/articles/building-babies-brains-early-childhood-development-infants-and-toddlers',
  0,
  52,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Managing Parental Stress and Burnout',
  'parental-stress-burnout-management',
  'Comprehensive strategies for recognizing, preventing, and managing stress and burnout in the parenting role, drawn from evidence-based stress management research.',
  E'# Managing Parental Stress and Burnout\n\nParenting is one of life''s most challenging roles, combining 24/7 responsibility with often limited resources and support. Parental stress and burnout are common experiences affecting mental health, relationships, and parenting quality. Recognizing and addressing stress is essential for family wellbeing.\n\n## Understanding Parental Burnout\n\nParental burnout differs from general stress; it represents a state of emotional exhaustion, reduced parenting efficacy, and emotional detachment from parenting role. Parents experiencing burnout feel depleted, helpless, and like their efforts don''t make a difference. This state reflects cumulative stress, inadequate recovery, and often lack of support.\n\nBurnout develops gradually, often unrecognized until it becomes severe. Early signs include irritability that seems disproportionate to triggers, persistent fatigue unrelated to sleep, cynicism about parenting, and difficulty finding joy in activities that previously brought pleasure.\n\n## Common Stress Sources\n\nSleep deprivation remains the most significant stressor in early parenting. The cumulative effect of months of fragmented sleep impairs judgment, emotional regulation, and stress tolerance. Infant sleep challenges create particular stress, especially if the infant has colic or reflux.\n\nFeeling isolated is another major stressor. Traditional extended family networks have diminished; many parents live far from their families of origin and may lack established community connections. Stay-at-home parents and those working from home may experience particular isolation.\n\nFinancial pressure—whether related to childcare costs, lost income during parental leave, or general family expenses—creates significant stress, particularly for lower-income families. The intersection of work demands and parenting responsibilities creates constant tension, especially for those without adequate flexibility.\n\n## Stress Management Strategies\n\nPrioritize sleep recovery, even imperfectly. If possible, arrange one night weekly where another caregiver handles all nighttime parenting while you sleep uninterrupted. Even one longer sleep period can significantly improve stress tolerance.\n\nBuild in breaks from parenting responsibilities daily. These need not be elaborate: 15 minutes of uninterrupted time for yourself—reading, showering, walking alone—provides recovery space. Communicate these needs to partners or family and protect this time deliberately.\n\nConnect with others navigating similar stages. Parent groups, online communities, or individual friendships with other parents normalize your experience and reduce isolation. Knowing others experience similar struggles provides relief and often practical problem-solving ideas.\n\nSet realistic expectations for housekeeping, cooking, and home maintenance. During intensive parenting stages, "good enough" household management is appropriate. Let go of perfectionism in areas that matter less than your own wellbeing.\n\nEngage in physical activity, even brief movement. Exercise reduces stress hormones and improves mood. Walking with a stroller, dancing with your child, or stretching during naps all provide benefits.\n\n## Professional Support\n\nTherapy provides valuable support for parental stress, particularly cognitive behavioral approaches that teach stress-management skills. Some therapists specialize in postpartum and parenting concerns.\n\nSupport groups specifically for parents—whether virtual or in-person—normalize struggles and offer practical suggestions. Many communities offer free or low-cost parenting groups.\n\n## When Stress Becomes Mental Health Concern\n\nIf stress is accompanied by depressed mood, anxiety, intrusive thoughts, or inability to function, professional mental health assessment is important. Postpartum depression, postpartum anxiety, and parenting-related anxiety disorders are treatable. Seeking help represents strength and is essential for family wellbeing.',
  'article',
  'https://www.apa.org/science/about/psa/parenting-stress',
  0,
  260,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Understanding Infant Crying and Colic',
  'infant-crying-colic-guide',
  'Evidence-based information about normal infant crying, colic causes and management strategies, and when to seek medical evaluation.',
  E'# Understanding Infant Crying and Colic\n\nCrying is infants'' primary communication method, yet it remains one of parenting''s most stressful challenges. Understanding the purposes of crying and distinguishing typical crying from colic helps parents respond effectively and manage their own stress.\n\n## The Purpose of Infant Crying\n\nCrying serves multiple functions: communicating hunger, discomfort, tiredness, overstimulation, or need for connection. Most crying has a clear cause and resolves once the need is addressed. Newborns typically cry 2-3 hours daily on average, with peaks around 6 weeks of age, gradually declining after 3-4 months.\n\nCrying is how infants express distress and request help. Responding to crying does not create "spoiled" babies; rather, responsive parenting teaches babies that their signals will be heard and met, building trust and security.\n\n## Distinguishing Normal Crying from Colic\n\nInfant colic refers to intense, prolonged crying in infants under 3 months of age without identifiable medical cause. The traditional definition (crying more than 3 hours per day, more than 3 days weekly) affects approximately 15-20% of infants.\n\nColic typically begins around 2-4 weeks of age and peaks around 6 weeks. Crying episodes are often intense and difficult to console. Colicky infants may draw their legs up, become red-faced, and appear to be in pain, though the actual cause of colic remains not fully understood.\n\nColic is NOT caused by poor parenting, inadequate feeding, or parental anxiety, though these factors may be blamed by well-meaning observers. Colic is NOT a sign of serious illness if the baby is otherwise healthy, eating well, and gaining weight.\n\n## Soothing Strategies\n\nResponse to crying should first address obvious needs: hunger, wet diaper, temperature discomfort, or need for sleep. Feeding a hungry infant, changing wet diapers, and ensuring appropriate temperature are primary interventions.\n\nPhysical soothing often helps: holding and gentle rocking, swaddling, white noise or soft sounds, pacifier use, and skin-to-skin contact all reduce crying in some infants. Different infants respond to different strategies; trying multiple approaches identifies what works for your specific baby.\n\nFor colicky infants, consistent soothing rituals provide comfort even if they don''t eliminate crying entirely. Some infants prefer being held upright; others prefer horizontal positions. Some respond to motion; others to stillness. Observation helps identify your baby''s preferences.\n\n## Managing Parental Response to Crying\n\nProlonged, inconsolable crying is extremely stressful for parents. Recognizing this normalizes your feelings and reduces guilt. Parental frustration or anger in response to crying does not make you a bad parent; it makes you human.\n\nIf you feel overwhelmed, it is safe and appropriate to put your baby in a safe place (crib, bassinet) and take a break. Stepping into another room, taking deep breaths, or calling a friend helps you regain composure. Never shake an infant, even in frustration, as this can cause serious brain injury.\n\n## When to Seek Medical Evaluation\n\nWhile most crying is normal, certain signs warrant medical evaluation: fever, lethargy, poor feeding, vomiting, constipation, diarrhea, rash, or breathing difficulty. If you''re concerned about your baby''s wellbeing beyond the crying itself, contact your pediatrician.\n\n## Colic Resolution\n\nColic is self-limiting; it resolves on its own by 3-4 months of age in nearly all infants. While colic is distressing, it does not cause long-term problems or indicate developmental delay. Most colicky infants develop normally in all respects.',
  'article',
  'https://www.healthychildren.org/English/ages-stages/baby/crying-colic/Pages/default.aspx',
  0,
  16,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Self-Care Strategies for New Parents',
  'new-parent-self-care-strategies',
  'Practical, evidence-based self-care approaches specifically designed for new parents navigating exhaustion, identity shifts, and competing demands.',
  E'# Self-Care Strategies for New Parents\n\nSelf-care is often misrepresented as luxurious bubble baths and spa days—unrealistic for most new parents. Genuine self-care during early parenting means attending to your physical, emotional, and mental health needs within realistic constraints. This foundation allows you to parent more effectively.\n\n## Physical Self-Care Fundamentals\n\nSleep remains the cornerstone of wellbeing. Even fragmented sleep compromises physical health and emotional resilience. Prioritize sleep recovery: nap when the baby naps, go to bed earlier when possible, and if feasible, arrange one full-sleep night weekly where you sleep uninterrupted while another caregiver manages nighttime duties.\n\nNutrition significantly impacts energy and mood. When cooking feels overwhelming, prioritize simple nourishing foods: hard-boiled eggs, nuts, fruit, cheese, yogurt, sandwiches, and leftovers provide nutrition without extensive preparation. Stay hydrated—drinking water consistently improves physical and cognitive function.\n\nMovement improves mood and stress tolerance. This need not mean formal exercise. Walking with a stroller, gentle stretching, dancing with your baby, or playing outside provides movement benefits. Aim for any movement daily rather than striving for intense exercise.\n\n## Emotional and Mental Self-Care\n\nName and validate your emotions. The transition to parenting involves joy alongside grief, anticipation alongside anxiety, love alongside resentment. These mixed feelings are normal. Accepting the full range of emotions rather than judging yourself for "negative" feelings reduces suffering.\n\nMaintain one-to-one connection with your partner or a trusted friend. Even 15 minutes of uninterrupted conversation—not about the baby or logistics—maintains adult connection and reminds you of your identity beyond parenting.\n\nEngage in at least one activity weekly that brings you joy or rest: reading, listening to music, a hobby, time in nature, or simply quiet time. These moments of recovery protect against burnout.\n\n## Setting Boundaries\n\nGive yourself permission to say no to requests that don''t align with your wellbeing. You cannot attend every social event, respond to every message instantly, or accept every unsolicited advice. Protecting your capacity is self-care.\n\nEstablish boundaries around unsolicited advice and criticism from family and others. You can respectfully decline feedback: "We''re doing what works for our family" is sufficient.\n\n## Managing Perfectionism\n\nAbandon expectations for how parenting "should" look. Fed is best for babies; let go of feeding method judgments. Children thrive in homes that are "good enough" rather than perfect. Prioritize what truly matters—your wellbeing, your baby''s safety and health—and accept lower standards in other areas.\n\n## Asking for and Accepting Help\n\nMost new parents need help but struggle to ask. Be specific in your requests: "Would you bring dinner Tuesday night?" works better than "Let me know if you can help." Accept help without obligation to clean the house or entertain visitors.\n\nFamily and friends often want concrete ways to support you. Asking for help is self-care and gives others the gift of supporting you meaningfully.\n\n## Professional Support\n\nTherapy is self-care. Talking with a professional about parenting stress, identity shifts, relationship changes, or mood concerns provides immense benefit. Some communities offer free or low-cost parenting-focused counseling.\n\n## Self-Compassion\n\nTreat yourself with the kindness you offer your child. You are learning to parent while sleep-deprived and managing significant life change. Growth happens imperfectly. Each day you show up for your child, even imperfectly, represents success.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.apa.org/science/about/psa/parenting-stress',
  0,
  52,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'When to Seek Help: Mental Health Resources for Parents',
  'parental-mental-health-resources',
  'Comprehensive guide to recognizing mental health challenges in parents and accessing evidence-based treatment and support resources.',
  E'# When to Seek Help: Mental Health Resources for Parents\n\nParental mental health directly impacts child development and family functioning. Yet parents often minimize their own mental health needs, viewing treatment as indulgent. Actually, addressing parental mental health is one of the most important things parents can do for their children.\n\n## Common Parental Mental Health Challenges\n\nPostpartum depression affects approximately 1 in 7 mothers. Symptoms include persistent depressed mood, loss of interest in activities, changes in sleep or appetite, difficulty concentrating, feelings of worthlessness or guilt, and sometimes thoughts of harming oneself or the baby.\n\nPostpartum anxiety disorders, including generalized anxiety, panic disorder, and obsessive-compulsive disorder, affect about 1 in 10 mothers. Symptoms include excessive worry, panic attacks, intrusive troubling thoughts, and compulsive checking or reassurance-seeking behaviors.\n\nPostpartum psychosis, while rare (affecting fewer than 1 in 500 mothers), represents a psychiatric emergency involving delusions, hallucinations, or loss of contact with reality.\n\nPaternal depression also occurs, affecting about 1 in 10 fathers. Symptoms may differ slightly, sometimes presenting as irritability, anger, or withdrawal rather than sadness.\n\n## Why These Conditions Occur\n\nPostpartum mood disorders result from complex interactions of biological factors (hormonal changes, sleep disruption, brain chemistry), psychological factors (stress, identity change, life adjustment), and social factors (lack of support, relationship stress, financial pressure). They are not caused by poor parenting, weakness, or failure to adapt. They are medical conditions requiring treatment.\n\n## Warning Signs\n\nSeek professional evaluation if you experience: persistent sadness or hopelessness lasting more than two weeks, inability to experience joy, significant sleep problems unrelated to the baby''s schedule, severe anxiety or panic, intrusive frightening thoughts, inability to care for yourself, feeling unable to care for the baby, thoughts of harming yourself or the baby, or feeling detached from your baby or partner.\n\n## Accessing Mental Health Care\n\nStart with your OB-GYN, midwife, or primary care doctor. Many providers screen for postpartum mood disorders and can provide initial assessment and referral. If symptoms are severe or you''re having thoughts of harming yourself or others, seek emergency mental health care immediately.\n\nPsychiatrists can provide medication evaluation and management. Therapists trained in postpartum mental health can provide cognitive behavioral therapy, interpersonal therapy, or other evidence-based approaches. Many communities now have specialized postpartum mental health clinics.\n\n## Treatment Options\n\nMedication, including antidepressants and anti-anxiety medications, is safe during breastfeeding. Most antidepressants pass minimal amounts into breast milk. Discuss options with your prescribing provider and lactation specialist.\n\nTherapy, particularly cognitive behavioral therapy and interpersonal therapy, has strong evidence for effectiveness. Some therapists offer virtual appointments, increasing access for those with childcare or transportation barriers.\n\nCombination treatment—medication plus therapy—is often most effective. Support groups, both virtual and in-person, provide community and normalize experiences.\n\n## Resources and Support Lines\n\nThe Postpartum Support International helpline (1-800-944-4773) provides free, confidential support and can help locate local resources. The National Maternal Mental Health Hotline (1-833-TLC-MAMA) offers free support for pregnant and postpartum individuals.\n\nManyMamas, Postpartum Support International, the American Perinatal Association, and the National Institute of Mental Health all provide evidence-based resources and provider directories.\n\n## Supporting a Partner with Mental Health Challenges\n\nIf your partner is struggling with maternal or paternal mental health concerns, encourage professional support without judgment. Offering specific help—"I''ll watch the baby Thursday afternoon so you can see your therapist"—demonstrates support. Educating yourself about the condition helps you understand it''s not personal rejection of you or the family.\n\n## Long-Term Outlook\n\nWith appropriate treatment, parental mental health disorders are highly treatable. Most parents recover completely and go on to parent successfully, with improved capacity for connection and emotional regulation after treatment. Seeking help is an act of love for yourself and your family.',
  'article',
  'https://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/publications/postpartum-depression-facts',
  0,
  260,
  'published',
  false
);

