INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Developmental Milestones: Birth to 3 Months',
  'milestones-birth-3-months',
  'Key developmental milestones for newborns and young infants, what to expect, and normal variation during the first three months.',
  E'The first three months are transformative as your baby transitions from newborn to early infant. Physical changes occur rapidly, and early reflexes give way to more deliberate movements. Understanding typical development helps you recognize progress and identify when your baby might need support.\n\n## Physical Development\n\nNewborns are born with various reflexes—automatic responses to stimuli—that indicate normal nervous system function. The Moro reflex (startle response), rooting reflex (turning toward touch on the cheek), and grasping reflex (gripping objects placed in the palm) are present at birth. Over the first 8-12 weeks, these reflexes gradually integrate as voluntary control develops. Your baby''s movements are initially jerky and uncoordinated; this is completely normal. By 8 weeks, movements become smoother and more intentional.\n\nHead control develops gradually. By 4 weeks, your baby lifts their head briefly when on their stomach. By 8 weeks, most babies hold their head up briefly during supported sitting. By 12 weeks, head control is more stable. Don''t be alarmed by initial wobbliness; the neck muscles are developing strength.\n\n## Social and Emotional Development\n\nNewborns cry to communicate all needs—hunger, discomfort, tiredness. Your response to crying isn''t spoiling; it''s teaching your baby that the world is responsive and trustworthy. By 4-6 weeks, your baby''s smile appears—initially a social smile emerging in response to human faces and voices. This smile is miraculous and transforms the parent-infant relationship. By 8-12 weeks, your baby clearly prefers familiar people and smiles broadly at familiar faces while being more cautious with strangers.\n\nYour baby begins cooing—soft vowel sounds—around 6-8 weeks. These early vocalizations are the foundation of language development. Respond to cooing enthusiastically; back-and-forth vocalizing teaches communication patterns.\n\n## Visual Development\n\nNewborns'' vision is blurry; they focus best at 8-12 inches—exactly the distance of a parent''s face during feeding and interaction. By 4 weeks, your baby tracks moving objects briefly. By 8 weeks, tracking becomes smoother and more extended. Color vision develops gradually; focus on high-contrast objects initially, then increasingly on colors. By 12 weeks, your baby shows preference for faces and complex patterns over simple shapes.\n\n## Sleep Patterns\n\nNewborns sleep 16-17 hours daily in short bursts without regard to day/night distinction. By 6-8 weeks, babies begin differentiating day and night, sleeping longer at night with increased awareness during day. By 12 weeks, some babies sleep for 5-6 hour stretches, though others still wake frequently. These patterns vary significantly; night sleeping isn''t a developmental achievement at this age but reflects individual temperament and needs.\n\n## Feeding Development\n\nNewborns need to feed 8-12 times daily. Breastfed babies typically feed more frequently than formula-fed babies due to easier digestion of breast milk. By 4-6 weeks, many babies begin to space feedings slightly. Feeding takes significant time (20-45 minutes) as your baby develops efficiency. By 12 weeks, feeding usually becomes faster as your baby''s latch and suckling improve.\n\n## Variation and Concerns\n\nInfants vary tremendously in development rate and temperament. Some babies smile early; others don''t until 8-10 weeks. Some sleep much more than others. Some cry rarely; others cry frequently. These variations usually reflect normal differences. However, contact your pediatrician if your baby isn''t tracking or responding to sound by 8-12 weeks, shows no social smiles or responsiveness by 12 weeks, seems extremely limp or extremely stiff, or isn''t feeding adequately. Most concerns resolve, but early identification allows intervention if needed.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/actearly/milestones/index.html',
  0,
  12,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Developmental Milestones: 4 to 6 Months',
  'milestones-4-6-months',
  'Developmental achievements between 4-6 months, including motor skills, communication, and cognitive growth during this rapid development period.',
  E'Between 4-6 months, your baby undergoes dramatic transformation. Physical capabilities expand significantly, and the baby who seemed immobile at 4 months shows increasing control and intention. Cognitive growth accelerates as your baby''s brain matures and makes new connections.\n\n## Motor Development\n\nBy 4 months, most babies hold their head steady and can briefly support weight on legs when held upright. Reaching becomes more coordinated; your baby reaches for and grasps objects intentionally rather than reflexively. By 5-6 months, many babies roll from back to side, and some roll completely. The progression of rolling from back to stomach typically occurs by 6 months. By 6 months, many babies sit with minimal hand support, though sitting independently usually comes later.\n\nYour baby''s hand-eye coordination improves dramatically. They track moving objects smoothly and bring objects to their mouth to explore. The mouth is the primary exploratory tool at this age; don''t be alarmed that everything goes in the mouth. Your baby is learning through taste, texture, and sensory input.\n\n## Communication Development\n\nBabbling becomes more complex and tuneful. Your baby produces varied syllables and increasingly imitates sounds they hear. Speech sounds emerge without yet forming recognizable words; this is normal and indicates healthy language development. Your baby communicates by varying cries, showing clear preference for familiar voices. By 6 months, many babies produce simple sounds like "ba," "ma," and "da," though these don''t yet mean words.\n\nYour baby''s comprehension advances significantly. They understand their name, recognize familiar people, and respond to simple words. Your baby shows awareness of tone; a gentle voice produces different responses than a stern voice. Language input during this period is crucial; babies exposed to more speech develop stronger language skills.\n\n## Cognitive Development\n\nBy 4-6 months, your baby demonstrates early signs of object permanence, understanding that hidden objects still exist. They may show expectation when a partially hidden toy disappears, beginning to search. By 6 months, your baby shows increased intentionality and beginning cause-and-effect understanding. They deliberately make sounds or movements to get responses, understanding that their actions create effects.\n\nYour baby shows increased interest in their surroundings and explores with mouth and hands. The world is becoming more understandable; patterns emerge in daily routines.\n\n## Social-Emotional Development\n\nBy 4 months, your baby shows social smiles readily and can make eye contact. They enjoy interaction and show preference for engaging people over toys. By 5-6 months, your baby shows clear preference for familiar people and may show early wariness of strangers—normal development indicating secure attachment. Your baby engages in back-and-forth interaction: you smile, they smile; you vocalize, they attempt to imitate.\n\n## Feeding Development\n\nAround 4-6 months, some babies show interest in foods beyond milk. Signs of readiness for starting solids include sitting with minimal support, showing interest in food, and ability to move food from front of mouth to back for swallowing. Introducing solids is developmental, not nutritional necessity; breast milk or formula continue providing primary nutrition. If introducing solids, single-ingredient foods (iron-fortified baby cereal, pureed vegetables or fruits) allow you to identify any sensitivities.\n\n## Sleep Development\n\nBy 4-6 months, many babies develop more consolidated sleep, potentially sleeping for longer stretches at night. However, significant variation exists; some babies continue waking multiple times. Sleep regression is common around 4 months as developmental changes occur. Maintaining consistent routines supports sleep development. By 6 months, capacity for sleeping through the night exists, though not all babies are ready; readiness is individual.\n\n## Variation and Concerns\n\nDevelopment varies significantly; your baby may show some milestones early and others later. However, contact your pediatrician if your baby isn''t reaching for toys by 5-6 months, isn''t making consonant sounds by 6 months, shows no preference for familiar people by 6 months, or has extreme difficulty rolling or supporting any weight. Early evaluation provides support if concerns exist.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/actearly/milestones/index.html',
  12,
  26,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Developmental Milestones: 7 to 12 Months',
  'milestones-7-12-months',
  'Key milestones during the second half of the first year, including crawling, word understanding, and major cognitive advances.',
  E'Between 7-12 months, development accelerates remarkably. Your baby progresses from limited independent movement to significant mobility, from pre-verbal communication to first words, from observer to active explorer. The transformation across this second half-year is profound.\n\n## Motor Development\n\nMobility emerges through varied paths. Some babies crawl (hands and knees), some bottom scoot, some army crawl, and some skip crawling entirely. Most babies develop some form of independent movement between 7-10 months. This mobility dramatically expands exploration and requires new safety measures. By 8-10 months, many babies pull to standing using furniture. By 10-12 months, some babies cruise along furniture or stand independently. Walking typically emerges between 12-15 months, though the range extends into the second year.\n\nSitting independently becomes stable by 8-9 months. Your baby can sit unsupported on the floor, though occasional toppling continues. By 12 months, sitting is secure and allows focused play with hands free. Fine motor development accelerates; your baby transfers objects hand to hand, uses pincer grasp (thumb and forefinger) to pick up small items, and brings objects to mouth and eyes.\n\n## Communication Development\n\nUnderstocking accelerates. By 7-8 months, your baby understands their name, simple words (\"no,\" \"bye-bye\"), and phrases ("Where''s daddy?"). By 10-12 months, comprehension expands significantly. Many babies respond to simple instructions ("Come here," "Where''s the dog?"). Babbling becomes more complex and varied, incorporating the sounds of your language. Around 10-12 months, many babies produce first recognizable words, though significant variation exists (some babies speak by 9 months while others don''t until 14-16 months).\n\nFirst words are typically highly familiar: familiar people''s names, favorite objects, or simple words like "no" or "hi." Celebrate these emerging words enthusiastically; your excitement motivates continued language development. Remember that your baby understands far more than they can express; receptive language far exceeds expressive language.\n\n## Cognitive Development\n\nObject permanence solidifies during this period. By 8-10 months, your baby clearly understands that hidden objects still exist and will search deliberately. Your baby shows cause-and-effect understanding, intentionally making sounds or movements to produce effects. By 10-12 months, your baby demonstrates problem-solving: they pull toys toward themselves using strings, remove obstacles to reach desired items, or try different approaches when one doesn''t work.\n\nYour baby shows increased intentionality and purposefulness. They play purposefully rather than randomly mouthing objects. Imitation becomes sophisticated; your baby imitates actions, words, and even gestures. This imitative learning is powerful for development.\n\n## Social-Emotional Development\n\nBy 7-8 months, stranger anxiety often emerges; your baby shows wariness of unfamiliar people. This isn''t concerning; it reflects secure attachment and developing awareness of social differences. By 9-12 months, your baby shows clear attachment to familiar people and distress at separation. Stranger anxiety gradually decreases with repeated exposure. Your baby shows preference for certain people and toys. Affection becomes more obvious; your baby may hug, kiss, or hold parents close.\n\n## Self-Awareness\n\nBy 8-10 months, your baby begins recognizing themselves in mirrors, though full self-recognition develops later. Around 12 months, your baby shows the beginning of understanding that they are a separate person with thoughts and desires. They point to show you things they find interesting, intentionally sharing experience. This shared attention represents sophisticated social development.\n\n## Play Development\n\nPlay becomes more complex. Rather than just mouthing objects, your baby engages in pretend play by the end of the year. They drink from toy cups, rock dolls, or pretend to eat. They enjoy games like peekaboo, which remain funny no matter how many repetitions. They engage in back-and-forth play with caregivers, taking turns and building on each other''s actions.\n\n## Feeding Development\n\nIf solids were started, your baby progresses from single-ingredient purees to textured foods and finger foods by 8-10 months. Self-feeding becomes possible; your baby feeds themselves with fingers or utensils, though efficiency is minimal. By 12 months, most babies eat family foods cut into safe sizes. They drink from cups with assistance. Feeding remains exploration and play in addition to nutrition.\n\n## Variation and Concerns\n\nDevelopment varies significantly; your baby may crawl early but speak late, or walk early with limited babbling. Most variation is normal. However, contact your pediatrician if your baby shows no interest in social interaction or play by 9-10 months, isn''t babbling or making varied sounds by 9-10 months, doesn''t respond to their name by 10 months, or shows no interest in mobile exploration by 10-11 months. Early intervention when developmental concerns exist provides valuable support.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/actearly/milestones/index.html',
  26,
  52,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'Developmental Milestones: 1 to 2 Years',
  'milestones-1-2-years',
  'Key developmental achievements during the second year of life, including walking, vocabulary expansion, and developing independence.',
  E'Between 1-2 years, development transitions from infancy to early toddlerhood. Language expands from first words to short phrases. Movement progresses from walking to running. Independence begins emerging strongly. The second year involves remarkable transformation across all domains.\n\n## Motor Development\n\nWalking independently is the hallmark of this year, though timing varies tremendously (12-18 months is typical, with wide normal variation). Initial walking is unsteady, wide-legged, and brief. Gradually, walking becomes steadier and distance increases. By 15 months, many toddlers walk with less wobbling. By 18 months, most toddlers walk with near-adult mechanics, though running takes further development. By 2 years, many toddlers run, jump (with both feet off the ground), kick balls, and climb stairs with alternating feet.\n\nStair climbing develops gradually. Initially, toddlers crawl up stairs. By 18 months, many climb up stairs with one hand held or railings gripped. By 2 years, many ascend stairs with alternating feet, though descending typically requires more assistance. Throwing and kicking emerge; toddlers throw objects (often in directions that delight them) and attempt kicking balls with varying success.\n\nFine motor skills develop significantly. Toddlers begin scribbling intentionally around 15 months. They use pincer grasp (thumb and finger) for feeding and manipulation. They turn pages of books, though not one at a time. They stack blocks, place shapes in sorters, and manipulate small objects. These activities develop hand-eye coordination and fine motor control.\n\n## Language Development\n\nVocabulary expands dramatically. Most toddlers have 5-50 words by 18 months and 50-200+ words by 2 years. The rate of vocabulary growth accelerates, particularly around 18-20 months, when many toddlers experience vocabulary explosion. Two-word combinations emerge around 18-24 months (\"more milk,\" \"daddy up,\" \"me go\"). By 2 years, simple sentences appear, though grammar remains immature.\n\nComprehension continues exceeding expression. Your toddler understands significantly more language than they produce. They follow simple, one-step instructions and understand much of what they hear. Your toddler''s name is clearly understood, and they respond to it consistently. Early pretend play involves language; your toddler talks to dolls, pretends to feed toys, and engages in narrative during play.\n\n## Cognitive Development\n\nPretend play becomes increasingly sophisticated. Your toddler engages in symbolic play: feeding dolls, having tea parties, pretending to drive cars. This capacity for pretend represents major cognitive advancement; it requires understanding that objects can represent other things. Your toddler shows cause-and-effect understanding and problem-solving. When something doesn''t work, they try different approaches.\n\nMemory develops. Your toddler remembers recent events and anticipates routines. They show understanding of time concepts (\"later,\" \"tomorrow\") though not with adult accuracy. Understanding of object properties develops; your toddler categorizes objects and understands that things have consistent characteristics.\n\n## Social-Emotional Development\n\nAutonomy becomes a driving force. The characteristic \"me do it\" and \"no\" of toddlers reflects emerging independence. Your toddler wants to do things themselves and becomes frustrated by limitations. Emotional expression becomes more varied; your toddler shows clear preferences, anger at restrictions, and affection toward loved ones. Tantrums may emerge, reflecting emotion exceeding regulation capacity.\n\nAttachment to specific people remains strong, and separation anxiety peaks in the second year. Your toddler may be clingy and reluctant to separate from you. This reflects secure attachment and is normal. Parallel play (playing alongside other children rather than with them) characterizes this age; true cooperative play typically comes later.\n\n## Self-Care Skills\n\nYour toddler becomes involved in self-care. Feeding with utensils is increasingly possible, though messy. Drinking from cups without lids improves. Diaper awareness begins; some toddlers show interest in toileting, though most aren''t developmentally ready. Hair and hand-washing with assistance becomes possible. Dressing is increasingly participatory; your toddler helps remove clothes and attempts putting on simple items.\n\n## Play Preferences\n\nToddlers enjoy varied activities. Balls (throwing, kicking, rolling), building with blocks, pretend play with dolls or kitchen items, exploring with pots and pans, and picture books are all engaging. Your toddler enjoys repetition; the same book read repeatedly and the same game played many times both delight toddlers. Outdoor exploration fascinates; your toddler loves examining grass, dirt, water, and natural materials.\n\n## Variation and Concerns\n\nDevelopment shows tremendous individual variation. Some toddlers walk at 11 months while others wait until 18 months; both are normal. Some have 100+ words at 18 months while others have 10-20; variation within normal range is wide. Contact your pediatrician if your toddler isn''t walking by 18 months, shows no interest in or use of pretend play by 18 months, isn''t saying any words by 18 months, seems to be regressing in any area, or shows significantly less social interest. Early intervention provides valuable support if concerns exist.',
  'guide',
  'https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/actearly/milestones/index.html',
  52,
  104,
  'published',
  false
);

INSERT INTO public.resources (title, slug, summary, body, resource_type, source_url, age_start_weeks, age_end_weeks, status, is_premium)
VALUES (
  'When to Talk to Your Pediatrician About Development',
  'pediatrician-developmental-concerns',
  'Guidance on recognizing developmental red flags, communication strategies with pediatricians, and resources for evaluation and support.',
  E'Parents often wonder whether their child''s development is on track. While developmental variation is normal and wide, some patterns warrant professional evaluation. Understanding red flags, communicating effectively with pediatricians, and accessing early intervention when needed supports optimal development.\n\n## Understanding Red Flags\n\nRed flags—early signs of potential developmental delay or disorder—exist across developmental domains. They don''t diagnose disorders; rather, they indicate that professional evaluation would be appropriate. Red flags vary by age. In the first year, red flags include: not turning toward sounds or voices, extreme disinterest in people, persistent extreme muscle tone issues (very floppy or very stiff), not grasping objects by 5-6 months, or extreme feeding difficulties.\n\nBetween 12-24 months, red flags include: no words by 18 months, not following simple instructions, no interest in pretend play by 18-24 months, significant repetitive behaviors, not pointing or showing shared interest by 15-18 months, or significant regression in any area. Behavioral red flags include extreme difficulty with transitions, excessive tantrums, or self-injurious behavior.\n\nImportantly, showing one potential concern doesn''t mean your child has a disorder. However, multiple concerns or significant concern about a specific domain warrant professional input. Parental instinct matters; if you''re concerned about your child''s development, that concern is worth discussing with your pediatrician.\n\n## Communication with Your Pediatrician\n\nApproach discussions without defensiveness or expectations of diagnosis. Frame concerns as observations: \"I''ve noticed that [specific observation], and I''m wondering if it''s something we should evaluate.\" Describe specific behaviors rather than general impressions. Instead of \"He''s not talking enough,\" say \"He has about 10 words at 20 months.\" Specific information helps pediatricians assess whether concerns are significant.\n\nAsk directly about red flags at well-child visits. Many pediatric practices use screening tools (standardized questionnaires about developmental milestones). These tools help identify children needing further evaluation. If your pediatrician doesn''t use screening tools, you can bring specific concerns. Come prepared with observations from different settings; development at home, in childcare, and with peers may vary.\n\n## Early Intervention Services\n\nPublic early intervention programs (in the US, typically from birth to age 3) provide free or low-cost evaluation and services for children with developmental delays or conditions. If your pediatrician refers to early intervention, this doesn''t mean something is wrong; it''s accessing evaluation to determine whether support is helpful. Early intervention is designed to support development; research demonstrates that services provided early, when the brain is most plastic, provide maximum benefit.\n\nEvaluation through early intervention is comprehensive and free. Evaluators assess developmental status in multiple domains: motor, cognitive, language, social-emotional, and adaptive. They compare your child''s development to age expectations and determine whether delay exists. If delay is identified, your family works with the early intervention team to develop an Individualized Family Service Plan (IFSP) specifying goals and services.\n\n## Private Evaluation Options\n\nIf early intervention isn''t appropriate or desired, private developmental or psychological evaluations are available. Developmental pediatricians, child psychologists, speech-language pathologists, and occupational therapists can provide comprehensive evaluation. These evaluations are typically thorough and helpful for identifying specific strengths and needs. However, they involve expense and may have wait times.\n\n## Supporting Development While Evaluating\n\nIf you have concerns about development, continue providing supportive interactions and activities while seeking evaluation. Your consistent responsiveness, play, conversation, and engagement support development regardless. If evaluation identifies delay, intervention services build on the strengths you''ve been developing. If evaluation doesn''t reveal significant delay, you''ve gained reassurance and specific information about your child''s development.\n\n## Developmental Variation is Normal\n\nReiterate that significant developmental variation is completely normal. Children develop at different rates; early achievement doesn''t predict later advantage, and later achievement doesn''t predict later disadvantage. Many children who seem to be developing more slowly in some areas catch up entirely by school age. The goal of early intervention isn''t to force acceleration; it''s to provide support so children can progress optimally.\n\n## Avoiding Over-Concern\n\nInternet searches about developmental delays can cause unnecessary worry. Remember that information found online describes populations and possibilities, not your individual child. Your pediatrician''s clinical assessment, considering your child''s specific history and context, is more valuable than online information. Avoid comparing children; each child has a unique developmental trajectory.\n\n## Resources\n\nProvide families with concrete resources: contact information for early intervention in your area, information about screening and assessment options, and support resources. Organizations like Zero to Three, CDC''s Act Early campaign, and condition-specific organizations provide information. Connecting families with other families who have navigated evaluation and support builds community and reduces isolation.',
  'article',
  'https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/actearly/concerned.html',
  0,
  260,
  'published',
  false
);

